{"title_page": "University of Alberta shooting", "text_new": "{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title       = University of Alberta shooting\n| image       = \n| image_size  = \n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| map         = \n| map_size    =\n| map_alt     =\n| map_caption = \n| location    = HUB Mall, [[University of Alberta]], [[Edmonton]], [[Alberta]], [[Canada]] \n| target      =\n| coordinates = \n| date        = {{Start date|2012|6|15}}\n| time        = 12:12 a.m.\n| timezone    = [[UTC\u221206:00|MDT]]\n| type        = [[Armed robbery]], [[workplace shooting]], [[Theft|heist]]\n| fatalities  = 3 \n| injuries    = 1 \n| victims     = <!-- or | victim      = -->\n| perpetrator = Travis Baumgartner\n| weapons     = [[.38]]-calibre [[revolver]] \n| numparts    = <!-- or | numpart     = -->\n| dfens       = <!-- or | dfen        = -->\n| motive      = Robbery \n| website     = <!-- URL|example.com}} -->\n}}\n\nOn June 15, 2012, 21-year-old security guard Travis Baumgartner, an employee of G4S Cash Solutions, shot four of his coworkers, three fatally, in the HUB Mall building on the campus of [[University of Alberta]] in [[Edmonton|Edmonton, Alberta]], Canada. He stole his employer's [[armored truck]] and money, and gave the cash or left it at the homes of his mother and two friends. Baumgartner was arrested the next day in [[British Columbia]], as he made plans to cross the U.S. border. \n\nOn September 9, 2013, Baumgartner plead guilty of three counts of murder, and on September 11, 2013, was sentenced to [[life in prison]] without the chance of [[parole]] for forty years, one of the longest or strictest prison sentences imposed on anyone in modern Canadian history. \n\n==Details==\n===Shooting===\nSeveral minutes into midnight, Baumgartner committed the crime while on duty at HUB Mall, a student residence and indoor food court, during a routine circuit with four coworkers to replenish [[Automated teller machine|ATMs]] around the city of Edmonton, as a part of their employment with G4S Cash Solutions. While refilling the [[TD Canada Trust|TD]] ATMs, Baumgartner shot three of his coworkers with a [[.38]]-calibre [[revolver]] as they entered the secured [[vault (architecture)|vault]] located behind the machines, before locking them inside. He then approached the [[armored car (valuables)|armored car]] they were using and shot and killed another co-worker. All of the four victims were shot in the back of the heads, at [[point blank]] range. He then stole the vehicle and fled the scene.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/travis-baumgartner-gets-40-years-without-parole-for-killing-co-workers-1.1706464|title=Travis Baumgartner gets 40 years without parole for killing co-workers|author=|date=September 11, 2012|publisher=[[CBC News]]}}</ref> \n\nThree of the workers died at the scene, while one survivor was brought to the hospital with critical injuries. The victims were Brian Ilesic, 35; Edgar \"Eddie\" Rejano, 39, and Michelle Shegelski, 26. A fourth guard, a male, was severely injured in the shootings, sustaining [[brain injuries]].<ref name=\"CBCPleads\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/travis-baumgartner-pleads-guilty-in-deadly-edmonton-shootings-1.1703929|title=Travis Baumgartner pleads guilty in deadly Edmonton shootings|author=|date=September 9, 2013|publisher=[[CBC News]]}}</ref>\n\n===Capture===\nA [[manhunt (law enforcement)|manhunt]] ensued as Baumgartner fled Edmonton, dropping off money for his two friends and mother. While at a friend's home, Baumgartner destroyed his cell phone so that it could not be used to track him. After eventually hearing news reports in the media, both friends notified police and returned the money. Baumgartner left [[Canadian dollar|$]]64,000 on his mother's kitchen table, and then left the Edmonton area. He swapped his licence plate for one from his mother\u2019s vehicle and drove away, heading west to the resort town of [[Banff, Alberta|Banff]]. There, he threw his weapon and vest into a river, and headed to the United States border, supposedly to [[Seattle, Washington]].<ref name=\"AgreedStatement\">{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/784867-travis-baumgartner-agreed-statement-of-facts/784867-travis-baumgartner-agreed-statement-of-facts_djvu.txt|title=Travis Baumgartner Agreed Statement of facts|author=|accessdate=March 31, 2020|work=Judicial District of Edmonton}}</ref> On June 16, 2012, 4:08 p.m. [[UTC\u221206:00|MDT]] (Edmonton time), Baumgartner was arrested by [[U.S. Customs and Border Protection]] while he was trying to cross the border at the Port of Lyndon near [[Langley, British Columbia (city)|Langley, British Columbia]] with $333,580 in cash.<ref name=\"CBCPleads\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/257229/edmonton-police-share-details-of-travis-baumgartners-arrest/|title=Edmonton Police share details of Travis Baumgartner\u2019s arrest|author=Mertz, Emily|date=June 17, 2012|work=[[Global News]]}}</ref>\n\n==Travis Baumgartner==\nAt the time of the shooting, Travis Brandon Baumgartner (born May 16, 1991)<ref name=\"AgreedStatement\"/> was living in [[Sherwood Park, Alberta]] with his mother. He has a sister, who he shares a father with.<ref name=\"CBCPleads\"/> Baumgartner had been hired by G4S Cash Solutions two months prior to the attack, and had no known disciplinary problems there. It is a requirement from the security agency to obtain a federal firearms licence, which includes a background check being run on the applicant.<ref name=\"TheStar\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2012/06/18/travis_baumgartner_passed_strict_screening_to_get_job_at_security_company.html|title=Travis Baumgartner: Passed strict screening to get job at security company|author=Wallace, Kenyon|date=June 18, 2012|work=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref> \n\nOn June 1, 2012, Baumgartner posted the following status post on his [[Facebook]] account: \u201cI wonder if I\u2019d make the six o\u2019clock news if I just started popping people off.\u201d<ref name=\"TheStar\"/> According to a friend, Baumgartner would tell him that he would rob his coworkers, in a jokingly manner. In a police interview, Baumgartner told a detective he did not get along with his coworkers, and that people at his workplace would ridicule him.<ref name=\"AgreedStatement\"/>\n\nAt the time of the shooting, Baumgartner had 26 cents in his bank account and owed $58,000 to his mother and two friends, due to debt over the purchase of a car and other items, and that he felt he needed to owe money to a friend due to years of being \"forked over\" money by him.<ref name=\"CBCPleads\"/><ref name=\"AgreedStatement\"/> \n\n==Trial and sentencing== \nSeveral days after the killings, Baumgartner confessed to an undercover [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] officer in a British Columbia jail cell, saying: \u201cI did it all. I killed those people and robbed their truck.\u201d<ref name=\"PostMediaNews\">{{cite news|url=https://o.canada.com/news/travis-baumgartner-40-years-no-parole|title=Travis Baumgartner gets life in prison with no chance of parole for 40 years|author=|date=September 11, 2013|work=[[Postmedia News]]}}</ref> On June 20, Baumgartner was flown in a RCMP aircraft to Edmonton, where he was taken into [[Edmonton Remand Centre]].<ref name=\"EdmontonJournal\">{{cite news|url=https://edmontonjournal.com/news/baumgartner-silent-during-first-court-appearance/wcm/ac6c8edc-0d1c-47c2-a4d4-047437b6b6ac/|title=U of A shooting: Baumgartner ordered not to contact family, G4S employees|author=Cormier, Ryan|date=June 12, 2012|work=[[Edmonton Journal]]}}</ref> The next day, Baumgartner appeared in court and was charged with three counts of [[first-degree murder]], one count of attempted murder, and four counts of robbery with a weapon.<ref name=\"CBC40Years\"/>\n\nOn September 9, 2013, Baumgartner pleaded guilty to the one charge of first-degree murder, for the death of Rejano, two counts of [[second-degree murder]] for the deaths of Ilesic and Shegelski, and a single charge of attempted murder. On September 11, he was sentenced by Associate Chief Justice John Rooke to [[life in prison]] without the possibility of [[parole]] for 40 years, until 2052. At the time of Baumgartner's sentencing, it was the harshest sentence imposed on anyone in the history of the Canadian judicial system, since the 1962 execution of [[Arthur Lucas]], who was convicted of killing a police officer in [[Toronto]].<ref name=\"CBC40Years\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/travis-baumgartner-gets-40-years-without-parole-for-killing-co-workers-1.1706464|title=Travis Baumgartner gets 40 years without parole for killing co-workers|author=<!-- Staff writer, no byline -->|date=11 September 2013|publisher=[[CBC News]]}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:2012 crimes in Canada|University of Alberta shooting]]\n[[Category:2012 mass shootings]]\n[[Category:2012 murders in North America|University of Alberta shooting]]\n[[Category:Attacks in 2012]]\n[[Category:2010s mass shootings in North America]]\n[[Category:Crime in Edmonton]]\n[[Category:Death in Alberta]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Alberta]]\n[[Category:History of Edmonton]]\n[[Category:June 2012 crimes]] \n[[Category:Murder in Alberta]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in Canada]]\n[[Category:Robberies of armored vehicles]]\n[[Category:Workplace violence]]\n[[Category:University and college shootings]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title       = University of Alberta shooting\n| image       = \n| image_size  = \n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| map         = \n| map_size    =\n| map_alt     =\n| map_caption = \n| location    = HUB Mall, [[University of Alberta]], [[Edmonton]], [[Alberta]], [[Canada]] \n| target      =\n| coordinates = \n| date        = {{Start date|2012|6|15}}\n| time        = 12:12 a.m.\n| timezone    = [[UTC\u221206:00|MDT]]\n| type        = [[Armed robbery]], [[workplace shooting]], [[Theft|heist]]\n| fatalities  = 3 \n| injuries    = 1 \n| victims     = <!-- or | victim      = -->\n| perpetrator = Travis Baumgartner\n| weapons     = [[.38]]-calibre [[revolver]] \n| numparts    = <!-- or | numpart     = -->\n| dfens       = <!-- or | dfen        = -->\n| motive      = Robbery \n| website     = <!-- URL|example.com}} -->\n}}\n\nOn June 15, 2012, 21-year-old security guard Travis Baumgartner, an employee of G4S Cash Solutions, shot four of his coworkers, three fatally, in the HUB Mall building on the campus of [[University of Alberta]] in [[Edmonton|Edmonton, Alberta]], Canada. He stole his employer's [[armored truck]] and money, and gave the cash or left it at the homes of his mother and two friends. Baumgartner was arrested the next day in [[British Columbia]], as he made plans to cross the U.S. border. \n\nOn September 9, 2013, Baumgartner plead guilty of three counts of murder, and on September 11, 2013, was sentenced to [[life in prison]] without the chance of [[parole]] for forty years, one of the longest or strictest prison sentences imposed on anyone in modern Canadian history. \n\n==Details==\n===Shooting===\nSeveral minutes into midnight, Baumgartner committed the crime while on duty at HUB Mall, a student residence and indoor food court, during a routine circuit with four coworkers to replenish [[ATM]]s around the city of Edmonton, as a part of their employment with G4S Cash Solutions. While refilling the [[TD Canada Trust|TD]] ATMs, Baumgartner shot three of his coworkers with a [[.38]]-calibre [[revolver]] as they entered the secured [[vault]] located behind the machines, before locking them inside. He then approached the [[armored car]] they were using and shot and killed another co-worker. All of the four victims were shot in the back of the heads, at [[point blank]] range. He then stole the vehicle and fled the scene.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/travis-baumgartner-gets-40-years-without-parole-for-killing-co-workers-1.1706464|title=Travis Baumgartner gets 40 years without parole for killing co-workers|author=|date=September 11, 2012|publisher=[[CBC News]]}}</ref> \n\nThree of the workers died at the scene, while one survivor was brought to the hospital with critical injuries. The victims were Brian Ilesic, 35; Edgar \"Eddie\" Rejano, 39, and Michelle Shegelski, 26. A fourth guard, a male, was severely injured in the shootings, sustaining [[brain injuries]].<ref name=\"CBCPleads\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/travis-baumgartner-pleads-guilty-in-deadly-edmonton-shootings-1.1703929|title=Travis Baumgartner pleads guilty in deadly Edmonton shootings|author=|date=September 9, 2013|publisher=[[CBC News]]}}</ref>\n\n===Capture===\nA [[manhunt]] ensued as Baumgartner fled Edmonton, dropping off money for his two friends and mother. While at a friend's home, Baumgartner destroyed his cell phone so that it could not be used to track him. After eventually hearing news reports in the media, both friends notified police and returned the money. Baumgartner left [[Canadian dollar|$]]64,000 on his mother's kitchen table, and then left the Edmonton area. He swapped his licence plate for one from his mother\u2019s vehicle and drove away, heading west to the resort town of [[Banff, Alberta|Banff]]. There, he threw his weapon and vest into a river, and headed to the United States border, supposedly to [[Seattle, Washington]].<ref name=\"AgreedStatement\">{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/784867-travis-baumgartner-agreed-statement-of-facts/784867-travis-baumgartner-agreed-statement-of-facts_djvu.txt|title=Travis Baumgartner Agreed Statement of facts|author=|accessdate=March 31, 2020|work=Judicial District of Edmonton}}</ref> On June 16, 2012, 4:08 p.m. [[UTC\u221206:00|MDT]] (Edmonton time), Baumgartner was arrested by [[U.S. Customs and Border Protection]] while he was trying to cross the border at the Port of Lyndon near [[Langley, British Columbia (city)|Langley, British Columbia]] with $333,580 in cash.<ref name=\"CBCPleads\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/257229/edmonton-police-share-details-of-travis-baumgartners-arrest/|title=Edmonton Police share details of Travis Baumgartner\u2019s arrest|author=Mertz, Emily|date=June 17, 2012|work=[[Global News]]}}</ref>\n\n==Travis Baumgartner==\nAt the time of the shooting, Travis Brandon Baumgartner (born May 16, 1991)<ref name=\"AgreedStatement\"/> was living in [[Sherwood Park, Alberta]] with his mother. He has a sister, who he shares a father with.<ref name=\"CBCPleads\"/> Baumgartner had been hired by G4S Cash Solutions two months prior to the attack, and had no known disciplinary problems there. It is a requirement from the security agency to obtain a federal firearms licence, which includes a background check being run on the applicant.<ref name=\"TheStar\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2012/06/18/travis_baumgartner_passed_strict_screening_to_get_job_at_security_company.html|title=Travis Baumgartner: Passed strict screening to get job at security company|author=Wallace, Kenyon|date=June 18, 2012|work=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref> \n\nOn June 1, 2012, Baumgartner posted the following status post on his [[Facebook]] account: \u201cI wonder if I\u2019d make the six o\u2019clock news if I just started popping people off.\u201d<ref name=\"TheStar\"/> According to a friend, Baumgartner would tell him that he would rob his coworkers, in a jokingly manner. In a police interview, Baumgartner told a detective he did not get along with his coworkers, and that people at his workplace would ridicule him.<ref name=\"AgreedStatement\"/>\n\nAt the time of the shooting, Baumgartner had 26 cents in his bank account and owed $58,000 to his mother and two friends, due to debt over the purchase of a car and other items, and that he felt he needed to owe money to a friend due to years of being \"forked over\" money by him.<ref name=\"CBCPleads\"/><ref name=\"AgreedStatement\"/> \n\n==Trial and sentencing== \nSeveral days after the killings, Baumgartner confessed to an undercover [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] officer in a British Columbia jail cell, saying: \u201cI did it all. I killed those people and robbed their truck.\u201d<ref name=\"PostMediaNews\">{{cite news|url=https://o.canada.com/news/travis-baumgartner-40-years-no-parole|title=Travis Baumgartner gets life in prison with no chance of parole for 40 years|author=|date=September 11, 2013|work=[[Postmedia News]]}}</ref> On June 20, Baumgartner was flown in a RCMP aircraft to Edmonton, where he was taken into [[Edmonton Remand Centre]].<ref name=\"EdmontonJournal\">{{cite news|url=https://edmontonjournal.com/news/baumgartner-silent-during-first-court-appearance/wcm/ac6c8edc-0d1c-47c2-a4d4-047437b6b6ac/|title=U of A shooting: Baumgartner ordered not to contact family, G4S employees|author=Cormier, Ryan|date=June 12, 2012|work=[[Edmonton Journal]]}}</ref> The next day, Baumgartner appeared in court and was charged with three counts of [[first-degree murder]], one count of attempted murder, and four counts of robbery with a weapon.<ref name=\"CBC40Years\"/>\n\nOn September 9, 2013, Baumgartner pleaded guilty to the one charge of first-degree murder, for the death of Rejano, two counts of [[second-degree murder]] for the deaths of Ilesic and Shegelski, and a single charge of attempted murder. On September 11, he was sentenced by Associate Chief Justice John Rooke to [[life in prison]] without the possibility of [[parole]] for 40 years, until 2052. At the time of Baumgartner's sentencing, it was the harshest sentence imposed on anyone in the history of the Canadian judicial system, since the 1962 execution of [[Arthur Lucas]], who was convicted of killing a police officer in [[Toronto]].<ref name=\"CBC40Years\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/travis-baumgartner-gets-40-years-without-parole-for-killing-co-workers-1.1706464|title=Travis Baumgartner gets 40 years without parole for killing co-workers|author=<!-- Staff writer, no byline -->|date=11 September 2013|publisher=[[CBC News]]}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:2012 crimes in Canada|University of Alberta shooting]]\n[[Category:2012 mass shootings]]\n[[Category:2012 murders in North America|University of Alberta shooting]]\n[[Category:Attacks in 2012]]\n[[Category:2010s mass shootings in North America]]\n[[Category:Crime in Edmonton]]\n[[Category:Death in Alberta]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Alberta]]\n[[Category:History of Edmonton]]\n[[Category:June 2012 crimes]] \n[[Category:Murder in Alberta]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in Canada]]\n[[Category:Robberies of armored vehicles]]\n[[Category:Workplace violence]]\n[[Category:University and college shootings]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:ATM\u2192Automated teller machine,vault\u2192vault (architecture),armored car\u2192armored car (valuables),manhunt\u2192manhunt (law enforcement)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_of_Alberta_shooting"}
{"title_page": "Crossover (David Cross and Peter Banks album)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Crossover\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[David Cross (musician)|David Cross]] and [[Peter Banks]]\n| cover      = David Cross and Peter Banks - Crossover.png\n| alt        =\n| released   = 17 January 2020<ref name=cherryred>{{cite web|url=https://www.cherryred.co.uk/product/david-cross-peter-banks-crossover-cd/|title=David Cross & Peter Banks: Crossover, CD}}</ref>\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = \n| length     =\n| label      = Noisy\n| producer   = Tony Lowe/David Cross\n| prev_title = \n| prev_year  = \n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n'''''Crossover''''' is an album by violinist [[David Cross (musician)|David Cross]] and guitarist [[Peter Banks]].<ref name=cherryred /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rockcellarmagazine.com/david-cross-and-peter-banks-crossover-album-prog-rock-king-crimson-yes-listen/|title=Out Now: David Cross and Peter Banks 'Crossover,' a Collaborative LP from King Crimson and Yes Icons (Listen)|date=24 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\nThe album is based on violin and guitar improvisations recorded on the afternoon of 10 August 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnewsradioonline.com/music-news/2020/1/27/various-yes-members-featured-on-new-collaborative-album-by-l.html|title=Various Yes members featured on new collaborative album by late Yes guitarist Peter Banks|website=ABC News Radio}}</ref> The two had met on a short joint tour in March 2006, featuring the David Cross Band and Peter Banks's Harmony in Diversity. Banks died in 2013 and Cross could not initially bring himself to return to the recordings. When he finally did, he worked with Tony Lowe and they invited in various musicians, largely with connections to [[Yes (band)|Yes]], of which Banks had been a member, or [[King Crimson]], of which Cross had been a member. Additional parts were recorded in 2018/9.<ref>''Crossover'' (noisy 010) liner notes by David Cross</ref><ref name=cherryred /><ref>\"Review: Crossover\", by Kris Needs, ''Prog'', issue 105, January 2020, p. 100</ref> Guest musicians were invited to \"interpret the music as freely and creatively as\" they wished.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ktlo.com/2020/01/27/various-yes-members-featured-on-new-collaborative-album-by-late-yes-guitarist-peter-banks/ |title=Various Yes members featured on new collaborative album by late Yes guitarist Peter Banks |website=KTLO LLC |date= |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n|title1=Rock to a Hard Place\n|writer1=[[David Cross (musician)|David Cross]]/[[Peter Banks]]\n|length1=9:12\n|title2=Upshift\n|writer2=Cross/Banks\n|length2=8:21\n|title3=The Smile Frequency\n|writer3=Cross/Banks\n|length3=5:17\n|title4=The Work Within\n|writer4=Cross/Banks\n|length4=4:28\n|title5=Missing Time\n|writer5=Cross/Banks\n|length5=4:10\n|title6=Plasma Drive\n|writer6=Cross/Banks\n|length6=6:05\n|title7=Laughing Strange\n|writer7=Cross/Banks\n|length7=7:23\n|title8=Crossover\n|writer8=Cross/Banks\n|length8=4:40\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\nCredits are adapted from the album's liner notes.\n\n===Musicians===\n*David Cross \u2013 violin\n*Peter Banks \u2013 guitar\n*[[Jeremy Stacey]] \u2013 drums (1, 7)\n*[[Geoff Downes]] \u2013 keyboards (1)\n*[[Tony Kaye (musician)|Tony Kaye]] \u2013 Hammond organ (2, 7)\n*[[Billy Sherwood]] \u2013 bass (2, 6)\n*[[Oliver Wakeman]] \u2013 Rhodes piano (2, 3, 6), grand piano (2), Moog synthesizer (2, 6), synthesizer (3), strings (6), organ (6)\n*[[Jay Schellen]] \u2013 drums (2)\n*Randy Raine-Reusch \u2013 world instruments (3)\n*[[Andy Jackson (recording engineer)|Andy Jackson]] \u2013 sound effects (4)\n*[[Pat Mastelotto]] \u2013 drums (6), drum synth (6)\n*Tony Lowe \u2013 additional bass, keys and string parts\n\n===Production===\n*Produced by Lowe/Cross\n*Adrian Benavides: sonic manipulation (6)\n*Mastered by Mike Pietrini\n*Artwork by Michael Inns\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{AllMusic | id= mw0003338679 | title= Crossover}}\n\n[[Category:2020 albums]]\n{{CI|date=March 2020}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Crossover\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[David Cross (musician)|David Cross]] and [[Peter Banks]]\n| cover      = David Cross and Peter Banks - Crossover.png\n| alt        =\n| released   = 17 January 2020<ref name=cherryred>{{cite web|url=https://www.cherryred.co.uk/product/david-cross-peter-banks-crossover-cd/|title=David Cross & Peter Banks: Crossover, CD}}</ref>\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = \n| length     =\n| label      = Noisy\n| producer   = Tony Lowe/David Cross\n| prev_title = \n| prev_year  = \n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n'''''Crossover''''' is an album by the violinst [[David Cross (musician)|David Cross]] and guitarist [[Peter Banks]].<ref name=cherryred /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rockcellarmagazine.com/david-cross-and-peter-banks-crossover-album-prog-rock-king-crimson-yes-listen/|title=Out Now: David Cross and Peter Banks 'Crossover,' a Collaborative LP from King Crimson and Yes Icons (Listen)|date=24 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\nThe album is based on violin and guitar improvisations recorded on the afternoon of 10 August 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnewsradioonline.com/music-news/2020/1/27/various-yes-members-featured-on-new-collaborative-album-by-l.html|title=Various Yes members featured on new collaborative album by late Yes guitarist Peter Banks|website=ABC News Radio}}</ref> The two had met on a short joint tour in March 2006, featuring the David Cross Band and Peter Banks's Harmony in Diversity. Banks died in 2013 and Cross could not initially bring himself to return to the recordings. When he finally did, he worked with Tony Lowe and they invited in various musicians, largely with connections to [[Yes (band)|Yes]], of which Banks had been a member, or [[King Crimson]], of which Cross had been a member. Additional parts were recorded in 2018/9.<ref>''Crossover'' (noisy 010) liner notes by David Cross</ref><ref name=cherryred /><ref>\"Review: Crossover\", by Kris Needs, ''Prog'', issue 105, January 2020, p. 100</ref> Guest musicians were invited to \"interpret the music as freely and creatively as\" they wished.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ktlo.com/2020/01/27/various-yes-members-featured-on-new-collaborative-album-by-late-yes-guitarist-peter-banks/ |title=Various Yes members featured on new collaborative album by late Yes guitarist Peter Banks |website=KTLO LLC |date= |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n|title1=Rock to a Hard Place\n|writer1=[[David Cross (musician)|David Cross]]/[[Peter Banks]]\n|length1=9:12\n|title2=Upshift\n|writer2=Cross/Banks\n|length2=8:21\n|title3=The Smile Frequency\n|writer3=Cross/Banks\n|length3=5:17\n|title4=The Work Within\n|writer4=Cross/Banks\n|length4=4:28\n|title5=Missing Time\n|writer5=Cross/Banks\n|length5=4:10\n|title6=Plasma Drive\n|writer6=Cross/Banks\n|length6=6:05\n|title7=Laughing Strange\n|writer7=Cross/Banks\n|length7=7:23\n|title8=Crossover\n|writer8=Cross/Banks\n|length8=4:40\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\nCredits are adapted from the album's liner notes.\n\n===Musicians===\n*David Cross \u2013 violin\n*Peter Banks \u2013 guitar\n*[[Jeremy Stacey]] \u2013 drums (1, 7)\n*[[Geoff Downes]] \u2013 keyboards (1)\n*[[Tony Kaye (musician)|Tony Kaye]] \u2013 Hammond organ (2, 7)\n*[[Billy Sherwood]] \u2013 bass (2, 6)\n*[[Oliver Wakeman]] \u2013 Rhodes piano (2, 3, 6), grand piano (2), Moog synthesizer (2, 6), synthesizer (3), strings (6), organ (6)\n*[[Jay Schellen]] \u2013 drums (2)\n*Randy Raine-Reusch \u2013 world instruments (3)\n*[[Andy Jackson (recording engineer)|Andy Jackson]] \u2013 sound effects (4)\n*[[Pat Mastelotto]] \u2013 drums (6), drum synth (6)\n*Tony Lowe \u2013 additional bass, keys and string parts\n\n===Production===\n*Produced by Lowe/Cross\n*Adrian Benavides: sonic manipulation (6)\n*Mastered by Mike Pietrini\n*Artwork by Michael Inns\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{AllMusic | id= mw0003338679 | title= Crossover}}\n\n[[Category:2020 albums]]\n{{CI|date=March 2020}}\n", "name_user": "HappyWithWhatYouHaveToBeHappyWith", "label": "safe", "comment": "spelling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crossover_(David_Cross_and_Peter_Banks_album)"}
{"title_page": "Disappearance of Don Lewis", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Disappearance of Don Lewis\n| image = Don Lewis disappearance portrait.jpg\n| image_size =\n| caption =\n| birth_name = Jack Donald Lewis\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1938|4|30|df=yes}}\n| birth_place =\n| other_names = Bob Martinez<ref name=\"Charley\">{{cite web|url=http://charleyproject.org/case/jack-donald-lewis|title=Jack Donald Lewis \u2013 The Charley Project|accessdate=April 1, 2020|date=September 22, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190927192040/http://charleyproject.org/case/jack-donald-lewis|archive-date=September 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| death_date = August 18, 2002 ([[legal death]])\n| disappeared_date = {{Disappeared date and age|df=yes|1997|8|18|1938|4|30}}\n| disappeared_place =[[Tampa]], [[Florida]], U.S.\n| disappeared_status = {{Missing for|1997|8|18}}\n| spouse             = {{Plainlist|\n* Gladys Lewis Cross<br />({{abbr|div.|divorce}} 1990)\n* {{marriage|[[Carole Baskin]]|1991|2002|end={{abbr|legal d.|legal death}}}}}}\n| children           = 4\n}}\n\n'''Jack Donald Lewis''' (April 30, 1938 \u2013 {{abbr|legal d.|legal death}} August 18, 2002) disappeared on August 18, 1997 after leaving his home in [[Tampa]], [[Florida]], United States.<ref name=\"WTSP\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wtsp.com/article/news/local/extras/disappearance-on-easy-street/67-396338130|title=Disappearance on Easy Street|website=WTSP|date=November 1, 2002|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> No evidence of Lewis being killed has surfaced and he was declared [[legally dead]] in 2002. As of 2020, the case is still open. Lewis' disappearance was covered in 2020 crime documentary series ''[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness]]'', which focused on a feud between Lewis' second wife [[Carole Baskin]] and private zoo owner [[Joe Exotic]].\n\n==Background==\nDon Lewis was a native of [[Dade City, Florida|Dade City]], [[Florida]], United States.<ref name=\"People\">{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/too-purrfect-vol-50-no-21/|title=Too Purrfect|date=December 7, 1998|accessdate=April 1, 2020|website=[[People (magazine)|People]]|author=Pam Lambert|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329014604/https://people.com/archive/too-purrfect-vol-50-no-21/|archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Lewis was a self-made millionaire by 1981 through the [[real estate]] and [[used car]]s businesses.<ref name=\"People\"/> By that time, Lewis was married to his first wife Gladys Lewis Cross<ref name=\"Kiro\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kiro7.com/news/trending/tiger-king-sheriff-seeking-leads-1997-disappearance-carole-baskins-2nd-husband/FCSINAFMEZD7TD6B64DBHL6GZA/|title='Tiger King': Sheriff seeking leads in 1997 disappearance of Carole Baskin's 2nd husband|website=[[KIRO-TV|KIRO 7]]|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref> and had three daughters and an adopted son.<ref name=\"People\"/> That year, Lewis first met [[Carole Baskin]] on Nebraska Avenue in [[Tampa]], Florida when she was nineteen years old.<ref name=\"Intel\">{{Cite web|url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2019/09/joe-exotic-and-his-american-animals.html|title= Joe Exotic bred lions, tigers, and ligers at his roadside zoo. He was a modern Barnum who found an equally extraordinary nemesis.|author=Robert Moor|date=September 3, 2019|accessdate=March 31, 2020|website=[[New York (magazine)|Intelligencer]]}}</ref><ref name=\"TheSecret\">{{Cite episode|title=The Secret|series=[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness]]|season=1|number=3|date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Baskin and Lewis engaged in an affair while both were still married.<ref name=\"TheSecret\"/> Baskin became one of Lewis' many girlfriends and she substantially grew his wealth by helping him buy and sell real estate in 1984.<ref name=\"People\"/> The couple divorced each of their spouses and married in 1991.<ref name=\"DBeast\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/joe-exotic-built-a-wild-animal-kingdom-he-was-the-most-dangerous-predator-of-them-all|title=Joe Exotic Built a Wild Animal Kingdom. He Was the Most Dangerous Predator of Them All.|website=[[The Daily Beast]]|date=June 22, 2019|accessdate=March 31, 2020|author=Sean Williams}}</ref>\n\nIn 1992, Lewis and Baskin co-founded Wildlife on Easy Street (now called [[Big Cat Rescue]]), a [[big cat]]s [[animal sanctuary]] in Tampa. According to Baskin and the 2020 crime documentary series ''[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness]]'', Lewis would take monthly flights to [[Costa Rica]] to deal with his [[Sexual addiction|sex addiction]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxygen.com/crime-news/what-happened-to-carole-baskins-ex-husband-don-lewis-from-tiger-king|title=What Happened To Carole Baskin's Former Husband, Who Vanished In 1997?|date=March 26, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020|website=[[Oxygen (TV channel)|Oxygen]]|author=Gina Tron}}</ref><ref name=\"Bible\">{{Cite web|url=https://brobible.com/culture/article/carole-baskin-boyfriend-restraining-order/|title=Carole Baskin\u2019s Boyfriend After Her Husband Disappeared Also Filed For A Chilling Restraining Order Against Her|author=Douglas Charles|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020|website=BroBible}}</ref> Lewis told family members and friends that he was planning to eventually move to Costa Rica.<ref name=\"People\"/> In early 1997, Lewis began transferring ownership of his properties in Florida to a Costa Rican company he controlled.<ref name=\"Charley\"/> In July 1997, Lewis filed a [[restraining order]] against Baskin, claiming that Baskin had threatened to kill him; the restraining order was rejected.<ref name=DonLewisMetro>{{Cite news |title=Tiger King: Who is Carole Baskin\u2019s first husband Jack 'Don' Lewis and when did he disappear? |url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/19/tiger-king-carole-baskins-first-husband-jack-donald-lewis-disappear-12423475/ |website=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] |date=March 19, 2020 |access-date=March 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326151850/https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/19/tiger-king-carole-baskins-first-husband-jack-donald-lewis-disappear-12423475/ |archive-date=March 26, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Lewis continued to live with Baskin afterwards.<ref name=\"WTSP\"/> Lewis told Baskin multiple times that he wanted a [[divorce]], but she did not think he was ever serious.<ref name=\"Charley\"/>\n\n==Investigation==\n[[File:Pilot Country Airport Gateway.jpg|thumb|left|Lewis' van was found at the Pilot Country Airport (pictured in 2016).<ref name=\"WTSP\"/>]]\nLewis disappeared on August 18, 1997 at around 6:00 a.m.<ref name=\"Charley\"/><ref name=\"WTSP\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wtsp.com/article/news/local/extras/disappearance-on-easy-street/67-396338130|title=Disappearance on Easy Street|website=WTSP|date=November 1, 2002|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> On August 20, 1997, Lewis' white 1989 Dodge van was found at the Pilot Country Airport in Springhill, Florida, forty miles away from the sanctuary.<ref name=\"People\"/><ref name=\"WTSP\"/> At the time of his disappearance, Lewis was known to own several planes and would fly them even though his [[private pilot licence]] was suspended.<ref name=\"Charley\"/> The keys to the van were found on the floorboard and the van had been parked for a couple of days.<ref name=\"WTSP\"/> No evidence was found within the van.<ref name=\"WTSP\"/> The [[Hillsborough County Sheriff's Office (Florida)|Hillsborough County Sheriff's Office]] \"found no sign of foul play\" at the Big Cat Rescue sanctuary and visited Costa Rica, where Lewis owned a 200-acre park, as part of their investigation.<ref name=\"People\"/><ref name=\"WTSP\"/><ref name=\"Poly\"/> The investigation in Costa Rica lasted five days.<ref name=\"Charley\"/> In Costa Rica, investigators only found indications that Lewis engaged in extramarital affairs and illegal business practices.<ref name=\"People\"/> None of Lewis' [[credit card]]s have been used since his disappearance.<ref name=\"People\"/>\n\nLewis left behind holdings estimated at more than [[United States dollar|$]]5 million, leading to a legal dispute between Baskin and Lewis' children.<ref name=\"People\"/> Lewis was [[Legal death|declared legally dead]] in 2002.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ew.com/tv/tiger-king-carole-baskin-slams-netflix-documentary/|title='Tiger King' subject Carole Baskin slams Netflix doc, calls it 'salacious and sensational'|website=EW.com}}</ref> Most of Lewis' estate was left to Baskin.<ref name=DonLewisMetro /> In 2011, Baskin refused to take a [[polygraph]] that was related to the investigation.<ref name=\"Poly\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/article/tiger-king-carole-baskin-don-lewis.html|title='Tiger King': What Happened to Carole Baskin\u2019s Husband, Don Lewis?|date=April 1, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020|website=[[The New York Times]]|author=Audra D. S. Burch}}</ref> The rest of Lewis' family has volunteered to take polygraphs.<ref name=\"Charley\"/> In 2020, the ''Tiger King'' series became popular as many people stayed at home due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2020 coronavirus pandemic]]. Using the popularity of ''Tiger King'', Hillsborough County Sheriff Chad Chronister appealed to the public for legitimate leads or evidence.<ref name=TampaSheriff>{{cite news|title=Hillsborough sheriff says tips are coming in \u2018Tiger King\u2019 missing millionaire case |author=Christopher Spata |url=https://www.tampabay.com/news/crime/2020/03/31/hillsborough-sheriff-says-tips-are-coming-in-tiger-king-missing-millionaire-case/ |website=[[Tampa Bay Times]] |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> Since the release of the series, the Hillsborough County Sheriff's Office has received six [[Tip (law enforcement)|tip]]s a day related to the disappearance.<ref name=\"Poly\"/> Chronister reiterated that his department doesn't \"have any type of evidence, not one piece, that suggests that [Lewis] was killed.\"<ref name=\"Poly\"/> The case is still open as of 2020.<ref name=\"CBS\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/police-ask-for-new-leads-in-disappearance-of-don-lewis-husband-of-tiger-king-star-carole-baskin/|title=Police ask for new leads in disappearance of Don Lewis, husband of \"Tiger King\" star Carole Baskin|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020|website=[[CBS News]]}}</ref>\n\n==Unofficial theories==\nIn December 1998, Pam Lambert of ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' wrote that there was \"a wealth of suspects and scenarios, but precious little evidence.\"<ref name=\"People\"/> The third episode of ''Tiger King'', \"The Secret\", covered multiple theories surrounding Lewis' disappearance. Lewis' children have pushed a theory that Baskin fed Lewis to the tigers, and have criticized investigators for not running a [[Genetic testing|DNA test]] on a [[meat grinder]] at the sanctuary.<ref name=\"People\"/> Baskin reacted to the allegations saying that there would be human bones as remains if the tigers would have eaten Lewis.<ref name=\"People\"/> Baskin expressed her disappointment about the theories to Lambert, saying \"Can you imagine having people think you killed your husband or wife and not being able to prove otherwise? Without a body, there is nothing I can do to clear my name.\"<ref name=\"People\"/> Baskin has a long-running feud with private zoo owner [[Joe Exotic]].<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Not Your Average Joe|series=[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness]]|season=1|number=1|date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Exotic has promoted an unsubstantiated theory that Baskin was involved in the disappearance of her Lewis.<ref name=\"CBS\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/police-ask-for-new-leads-in-disappearance-of-don-lewis-husband-of-tiger-king-star-carole-baskin/|title=Police ask for new leads in disappearance of Don Lewis, husband of \"Tiger King\" star Carole Baskin|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020|website=[[CBS News]]}}</ref> Exotic created a music video entitled \"Here Kitty Kitty\" that had a Baskin-lookalike feed raw meat to tigers.<ref name=\"Kiro\"/>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n[[Category:1990s missing person cases]]\n[[Category:August 1997 crimes]]\n[[Category:August 1997 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:Unsolved crimes in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Under construction|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Disappearance of Don Lewis\n| image = Don Lewis disappearance portrait.jpg\n| image_size =\n| caption =\n| birth_name = Jack Donald Lewis\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1938|4|30|df=yes}}\n| birth_place =\n| other_names = Bob Martinez<ref name=\"Charley\">{{cite web|url=http://charleyproject.org/case/jack-donald-lewis|title=Jack Donald Lewis \u2013 The Charley Project|accessdate=April 1, 2020|date=September 22, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190927192040/http://charleyproject.org/case/jack-donald-lewis|archive-date=September 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| death_date = August 18, 2002 ([[legal death]])\n| disappeared_date = {{Disappeared date and age|df=yes|1997|8|18|1938|4|30}}\n| disappeared_place =[[Tampa]], [[Florida]], U.S.\n| disappeared_status = {{Missing for|1997|8|18}}\n| spouse             = {{Plainlist|\n* Gladys Lewis Cross<br />({{abbr|div.|divorce}} 1990)\n* {{marriage|[[Carole Baskin]]|1991|2002|end={{abbr|legal d.|legal death}}}}}}\n| children           = 4\n}}\n\n'''Jack Donald Lewis''' (April 30, 1938 \u2013 {{abbr|legal d.|legal death}} August 18, 2002) disappeared on August 18, 1997 after leaving his home in [[Tampa]], [[Florida]], United States.<ref name=\"WTSP\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wtsp.com/article/news/local/extras/disappearance-on-easy-street/67-396338130|title=Disappearance on Easy Street|website=WTSP|date=November 1, 2002|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> No evidence of Lewis being killed has surfaced and he was declared [[legally dead]] in 2002. As of 2020, the case is still open. Lewis' disappearance was covered in 2020 crime documentary series ''[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness]]'', which focused on a feud between Lewis' second wife [[Carole Baskin]] and private zoo owner [[Joe Exotic]].\n\n==Background==\nDon Lewis was a native of [[Dade City, Florida|Dade City]], [[Florida]], United States.<ref name=\"People\">{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/too-purrfect-vol-50-no-21/|title=Too Purrfect|date=December 7, 1998|accessdate=April 1, 2020|website=[[People (magazine)|People]]|author=Pam Lambert|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329014604/https://people.com/archive/too-purrfect-vol-50-no-21/|archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Lewis was a self-made millionaire by 1981 through the [[real estate]] and [[used car]]s businesses.<ref name=\"People\"/> By that time, Lewis was married to his first wife Gladys Lewis Cross<ref name=\"Kiro\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kiro7.com/news/trending/tiger-king-sheriff-seeking-leads-1997-disappearance-carole-baskins-2nd-husband/FCSINAFMEZD7TD6B64DBHL6GZA/|title='Tiger King': Sheriff seeking leads in 1997 disappearance of Carole Baskin's 2nd husband|website=[[KIRO-TV|KIRO 7]]|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref> and had three daughters and an adopted son.<ref name=\"People\"/> That year, Lewis first met [[Carole Baskin]] on Nebraska Avenue in [[Tampa]], Florida when she was nineteen years old.<ref name=\"Intel\">{{Cite web|url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2019/09/joe-exotic-and-his-american-animals.html|title= Joe Exotic bred lions, tigers, and ligers at his roadside zoo. He was a modern Barnum who found an equally extraordinary nemesis.|author=Robert Moor|date=September 3, 2019|accessdate=March 31, 2020|website=[[New York (magazine)|Intelligencer]]}}</ref><ref name=\"TheSecret\">{{Cite episode|title=The Secret|series=[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness]]|season=1|number=3|date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Baskin and Lewis engaged in an affair while both were still married.<ref name=\"TheSecret\"/> Baskin became one of Lewis' many girlfriends and she substantially grew his wealth by helping him buy and sell real estate in 1984.<ref name=\"People\"/> The couple divorced each of their spouses and married in 1991.<ref name=\"DBeast\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/joe-exotic-built-a-wild-animal-kingdom-he-was-the-most-dangerous-predator-of-them-all|title=Joe Exotic Built a Wild Animal Kingdom. He Was the Most Dangerous Predator of Them All.|website=[[The Daily Beast]]|date=June 22, 2019|accessdate=March 31, 2020|author=Sean Williams}}</ref>\n\nIn 1992, Lewis and Baskin co-founded Wildlife on Easy Street (now called [[Big Cat Rescue]]), a [[big cat]]s [[animal sanctuary]] in Tampa. According to Baskin and the 2020 crime documentary series ''[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness]]'', Lewis would take monthly flights to [[Costa Rica]] to deal with his [[Sexual addiction|sex addiction]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxygen.com/crime-news/what-happened-to-carole-baskins-ex-husband-don-lewis-from-tiger-king|title=What Happened To Carole Baskin's Former Husband, Who Vanished In 1997?|date=March 26, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020|website=[[Oxygen (TV channel)|Oxygen]]|author=Gina Tron}}</ref><ref name=\"Bible\">{{Cite web|url=https://brobible.com/culture/article/carole-baskin-boyfriend-restraining-order/|title=Carole Baskin\u2019s Boyfriend After Her Husband Disappeared Also Filed For A Chilling Restraining Order Against Her|author=Douglas Charles|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020|website=BroBible}}</ref> Lewis told family members and friends that he was planning to eventually move to Costa Rica.<ref name=\"People\"/> In early 1997, Lewis began transferring ownership of his properties in Florida to a Costa Rican company he controlled.<ref name=\"Charley\"/> In July 1997, Lewis filed a [[restraining order]] against Baskin, claiming that Baskin had threatened to kill him; the restraining order was rejected.<ref name=DonLewisMetro>{{Cite news |title=Tiger King: Who is Carole Baskin\u2019s first husband Jack 'Don' Lewis and when did he disappear? |url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/19/tiger-king-carole-baskins-first-husband-jack-donald-lewis-disappear-12423475/ |website=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] |date=March 19, 2020 |access-date=March 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326151850/https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/19/tiger-king-carole-baskins-first-husband-jack-donald-lewis-disappear-12423475/ |archive-date=March 26, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Lewis continued to live with Baskin afterwards.<ref name=\"WTSP\"/> Lewis told Baskin multiple times that he wanted a [[divorce]], but she did not think he was ever serious.<ref name=\"Charley\"/>\n\n==Investigation==\n[[File:Pilot Country Airport Gateway.jpg|thumb|left|Lewis' van was found at the Pilot Country Airport (pictured in 2016).<ref name=\"WTSP\"/>]]\nLewis disappeared on August 18, 1997 at around 6:00 a.m.<ref name=\"Charley\"/><ref name=\"WTSP\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wtsp.com/article/news/local/extras/disappearance-on-easy-street/67-396338130|title=Disappearance on Easy Street|website=WTSP|date=November 1, 2002|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> On August 20, 1997, Lewis' white 1989 Dodge van was found at the Pilot Country Airport in Springhill, Florida, forty miles away from the sanctuary.<ref name=\"People\"/><ref name=\"WTSP\"/> At the time of his disappearance, Lewis was known to own several planes and would fly them even though his [[private pilot licence]] was suspended.<ref name=\"Charley\"/> The keys to the van were found on the floorboard and the van had been parked for a couple of days.<ref name=\"WTSP\"/> No evidence was found within the van.<ref name=\"WTSP\"/> The [[Hillsborough County Sheriff's Office (Florida)|Hillsborough County Sheriff's Office]] \"found no sign of foul play\" at the Big Cat Rescue sanctuary and visited Costa Rica, where Lewis owned a 200-acre park, as part of their investigation.<ref name=\"People\"/><ref name=\"WTSP\"/><ref name=\"Poly\"/> The investigation in Costa Rica lasted five days.<ref name=\"Charley\"/> In Costa Rica, investigators only found indications that Lewis engaged in extramarital affairs and illegal business practices.<ref name=\"People\"/> None of Lewis' [[credit card]]s have been used since his disappearance.<ref name=\"People\"/>\n\nLewis left behind holdings estimated at more than [[United States dollar|$]]5 million, leading to a legal dispute between Baskin and Lewis' children.<ref name=\"People\"/> Lewis was [[Legal death|declared legally dead]] in 2002.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ew.com/tv/tiger-king-carole-baskin-slams-netflix-documentary/|title='Tiger King' subject Carole Baskin slams Netflix doc, calls it 'salacious and sensational'|website=EW.com}}</ref> Most of Lewis' estate was left to Baskin.<ref name=DonLewisMetro /> In 2011, Baskin refused to take a [[polygraph]] that was related to the investigation.<ref name=\"Poly\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/article/tiger-king-carole-baskin-don-lewis.html|title='Tiger King': What Happened to Carole Baskin\u2019s Husband, Don Lewis?|date=April 1, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020|website=[[The New York Times]]|author=Audra D. S. Burch}}</ref> The rest of Lewis' family has volunteered to take polygraphs.<ref name=\"Charley\"/> In 2020, the ''Tiger King'' series became popular as many people stayed at home due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2020 coronavirus pandemic]]. Using the popularity of ''Tiger King'', Hillsborough County Sheriff Chad Chronister appealed to the public for legitimate leads or evidence.<ref name=TampaSheriff>{{cite news|title=Hillsborough sheriff says tips are coming in \u2018Tiger King\u2019 missing millionaire case |author=Christopher Spata |url=https://www.tampabay.com/news/crime/2020/03/31/hillsborough-sheriff-says-tips-are-coming-in-tiger-king-missing-millionaire-case/ |website=[[Tampa Bay Times]] |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> Since the release of the series, the Hillsborough County Sheriff's Office has received six [[Tip (law enforcement)|tip]]s a day related to the disappearance.<ref name=\"Poly\"/> Chronister reiterated that his department doesn't \"have any type of evidence, not one piece, that suggests that [Lewis] was killed.\"<ref name=\"Poly\"/> The case is still open as of 2020.<ref name=\"CBS\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/police-ask-for-new-leads-in-disappearance-of-don-lewis-husband-of-tiger-king-star-carole-baskin/|title=Police ask for new leads in disappearance of Don Lewis, husband of \"Tiger King\" star Carole Baskin|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020|website=[[CBS News]]}}</ref>\n\n==Unofficial theories==\nIn December 1998, Pam Lambert of ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' wrote that there was \"a wealth of suspects and scenarios, but precious little evidence.\"<ref name=\"People\"/> The third episode of ''Tiger King'', \"The Secret\", covered multiple theories surrounding Lewis' disappearance. Lewis' children have pushed a theory that Baskin fed Lewis to the tigers, and have criticized investigators for not running a [[Genetic testing|DNA test]] on a [[meat grinder]] at the sanctuary.<ref name=\"People\"/> Baskin reacted to the allegations saying that there would be human bones as remains if the tigers would have eaten Lewis.<ref name=\"People\"/> Baskin expressed her disappointment about the theories to Lambert, saying \"Can you imagine having people think you killed your husband or wife and not being able to prove otherwise? Without a body, there is nothing I can do to clear my name.\"<ref name=\"People\"/> Baskin has a long-running feud with private zoo owner [[Joe Exotic]].<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Not Your Average Joe|series=[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness]]|season=1|number=1|date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Exotic has promoted an unsubstantiated theory that Baskin was involved in the disappearance of her Lewis.<ref name=\"CBS\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/police-ask-for-new-leads-in-disappearance-of-don-lewis-husband-of-tiger-king-star-carole-baskin/|title=Police ask for new leads in disappearance of Don Lewis, husband of \"Tiger King\" star Carole Baskin|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020|website=[[CBS News]]}}</ref> Exotic created a music video entitled \"Here Kitty Kitty\" that had a Baskin-lookalike feed raw meat to tigers.<ref name=\"Kiro\"/>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n[[Category:1990s missing person cases]]\n[[Category:August 1997 crimes]]\n[[Category:August 1997 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:Unsolved crimes in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Nice4What", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Disappearance_of_Don_Lewis"}
{"title_page": "Alaska Communications", "text_new": "{{About|the current telecommunications company|the historical \"Alaska Communications\"|Alaska Communications System (ACS)}}\n{{Infobox company\n|logo=Acs header logo.png\n|name = Alaska Communications\n|type = [[Public company|Public]]\n|traded_as = {{NASDAQ|ALSK}}<br>[[Russell Microcap Index]] component\n|foundation = [[Anchorage, Alaska]] (1998)<ref name=\"founding\">{{cite web | url=http://investors.alsk.com/ReleaseDetail.cfm?ReleaseID=117995 | title=ACS Alaska Press Release Introducing New CEO | accessdate=2006-12-01 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070703084218/http://investors.alsk.com/ReleaseDetail.cfm?ReleaseID=117995 | archive-date=2007-07-03 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|location = Anchorage, Alaska\n|key_people = Bill Bishop, President and CEO\n|industry = [[Telecommunications]]\n|homepage = [http://www.alaskacommunications.com/ www.alaskacommunications.com]\n}}\n\n'''Alaska Communications''' (formerly '''Alaska Communications Systems''' or '''ACS''') is a [[telecommunications]] corporation headquartered in [[Anchorage, Alaska]]. It was the first telecommunications provider in the state of Alaska to maintain a [[3G|third-generation wireless]] network and the only provider in Alaska that owned fully incorporated infrastructure for the major telecommunications platforms; wireless communications, Internet networking, and local and long-distance phone service. Alaska Communications wireline operations include advanced data networks and an underwater fiber optic system. The Alaska Communications wireless operations included a statewide [[3G]] [[CDMA]] network, and coverage extended from the North Slope to Southeast Alaska.\n\n==History==\nThe company was formed in 1998, when [[CenturyLink|CenturyTel]] announced the sale of its Alaska operations (newly acquired from [[PacifiCorp]]) to local management and [[Fox Paine & Company]].<ref>{{Cite news| issn = 0362-4331| title = COMPANY NEWS; CENTURY TELEPHONE TO SELL ALASKA OPERATIONS| work = The New York Times| accessdate = 2015-05-23| date = 1998-08-18| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1998/08/18/business/company-news-century-telephone-to-sell-alaska-operations.html}}</ref> In 1999, Alaska Communications acquired Anchorage Telephone Utility from the [[Anchorage, Alaska|Municipality of Anchorage]].<ref>{{Cite web| title = Fox Paine & Company's Alaska Communications Systems to Acquire Anchorage Telephone Utility| accessdate = 2015-05-23| url = http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/fox-paine--companys-alaska-communications-systems-to-acquire-anchorage-telephone-utility-77086617.html}}</ref>\n\nOn February 3, 2014, Alaska Communications announced its purchase of TekMate.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://investors.alsk.com/releasedetail.cfm?ReleaseID=822747 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2017-08-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170830061508/http://investors.alsk.com/releasedetail.cfm?ReleaseID=822747 |archive-date=2017-08-30 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nOn December 4, 2014, [[General Communication#Wireless Telephone|GCI Wireless]] agreed to purchase the wireless assets of Alaska Communications for $300 million. The deal was completed in the first quarter of 2015.<ref>http://www.alaskacommunications.com/-/media/Files/Press-Releases/2015/ALSK_News_2015_2_2_General-(1).pdf</ref>\n\n==Current Projects==\nOn May 25, 2017, Alaska Communications announced it will be offering Internet services via [[OneWeb]].<ref>http://www.alaskacommunications.com/-/media/Files/Press-Releases/2017/ALSK_News_2017_5_25_General.pdf</ref>\n\nAlaska Communications has an agreement with Quintillion to use its submarine fiber optic cable to bring new services to some of Alaska's northernmost communities: [[Utqia\u0121vik]], [[Nome, Alaska|Nome]], [[Kotzebue]], [[Point Hope]] and [[Wainwright]].<ref>http://www.alaskacommunications.com/-/media/Files/Press-Releases/2017/ALSK_News_2017_3_8_General.pdf</ref>\n\n==Business Technology Center==\nOn June 9, 2016, Alaska Communications opened the Business Technology Center. The meeting space is open to community members, businesses, nonprofits and education organizations. It is located at 600 East 36th Ave, Anchorage, Alaska.<ref>http://www.alaskacommunications.com/-/media/Files/Press-Releases/2016/BTC-Press-Release-2016_06_08.pdf</ref>\n\n[[File:BTC8292017.jpg|thumb|Business Technology Center located in Anchorage, Alaska.]]\n\n==Community Work==\nAlaska Communications supports [[United Way]], [[Junior Achievement]], the [[University of Alaska]], 90% by 2020, and FIRST in Alaska.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.alaskacommunications.com/About/Our-Work-in-the-Community | title=Our Work in the Community - Alaska Communications}}</ref> It also partners with [[Boys & Girls Clubs of America|Boys & Girls Clubs]] \u2013 Alaska to put on Summer of Heroes, a program which awards scholarships to youth who are engaged in community service.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.alaskacommunications.com/About/Summer-of-Heroes | title=Summer of Heroes - Alaska Communications}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n<!-- Do not add forum, reseller, spam links to this article -->\n* {{Official website |http://www.alaskacommunications.com/}}\n\n{{Finance links\n| name = Alaska Communications Group Inc\n| symbol = ALSK\n| sec_cik = 1089511\n| hoovers = Alaska_Communications_Systems_Group_Inc.9c01f8c592398607\n}}\n{{United States telephone companies}}\n{{US mobile phone companies}}\n\n[[Category:Communications in Alaska]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Anchorage, Alaska]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:1998 establishments in Alaska]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications companies established in 1998]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 1998]]\n\n\n{{US-telecom-company-stub}}\n{{Alaska-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{About|the current telecommunications company|the historical \"Alaska Communications\"|Alaska Communications System (ACS)}}\n{{Infobox company\n|logo=Acs header logo.png\n|name = Alaska Communications\n|type = [[Public company|Public]]\n|traded_as = {{NASDAQ|ALSK}}<br>[[Russell Microcap Index]] component\n|foundation = [[Anchorage, Alaska]] (1998)<ref name=\"founding\">{{cite web | url=http://investors.alsk.com/ReleaseDetail.cfm?ReleaseID=117995 | title=ACS Alaska Press Release Introducing New CEO | accessdate=2006-12-01 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070703084218/http://investors.alsk.com/ReleaseDetail.cfm?ReleaseID=117995 | archive-date=2007-07-03 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|location = Anchorage, Alaska\n|key_people = Bill Bishop, President and CEO\n|industry = [[Telecommunications]]\n|homepage = [http://www.alaskacommunications.com/ www.alaskacommunications.com]\n}}\n\n'''Alaska Communications''' (formerly '''Alaska Communications Systems''' or '''ACS''') is a [[telecommunications]] corporation headquartered in [[Anchorage, Alaska]]. It was the first telecommunications provider in the state of Alaska to maintain a [[3G|third-generation wireless]] network and the only provider in Alaska that owned fully incorporated infrastructure for the major telecommunications platforms; wireless communications, Internet networking, and local and long distance phone service. Alaska Communications wireline operations include advanced data networks and an underwater fiber optic system. The Alaska Communications wireless operations included a statewide [[3G]] [[CDMA]] network, and coverage extended from the North Slope to Southeast Alaska.\n\n==History==\nThe company was formed in 1998, when [[CenturyLink|CenturyTel]] announced the sale of its Alaska operations (newly acquired from [[PacifiCorp]]) to local management and [[Fox Paine & Company]].<ref>{{Cite news| issn = 0362-4331| title = COMPANY NEWS; CENTURY TELEPHONE TO SELL ALASKA OPERATIONS| work = The New York Times| accessdate = 2015-05-23| date = 1998-08-18| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1998/08/18/business/company-news-century-telephone-to-sell-alaska-operations.html}}</ref> In 1999, Alaska Communications acquired Anchorage Telephone Utility from the [[Anchorage, Alaska|Municipality of Anchorage]].<ref>{{Cite web| title = Fox Paine & Company's Alaska Communications Systems to Acquire Anchorage Telephone Utility| accessdate = 2015-05-23| url = http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/fox-paine--companys-alaska-communications-systems-to-acquire-anchorage-telephone-utility-77086617.html}}</ref>\n\nOn February 3, 2014, Alaska Communications announced its purchase of TekMate.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://investors.alsk.com/releasedetail.cfm?ReleaseID=822747 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2017-08-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170830061508/http://investors.alsk.com/releasedetail.cfm?ReleaseID=822747 |archive-date=2017-08-30 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nOn December 4, 2014, [[General Communication#Wireless Telephone|GCI Wireless]] agreed to purchase the wireless assets of Alaska Communications for $300 million. The deal was completed in the first quarter of 2015.<ref>http://www.alaskacommunications.com/-/media/Files/Press-Releases/2015/ALSK_News_2015_2_2_General-(1).pdf</ref>\n\n==Current Projects==\nOn May 25, 2017, Alaska Communications announced it will be offering Internet services via [[OneWeb]].<ref>http://www.alaskacommunications.com/-/media/Files/Press-Releases/2017/ALSK_News_2017_5_25_General.pdf</ref>\n\nAlaska Communications has an agreement with Quintillion to use its submarine fiber optic cable to bring new services to some of Alaska\u2019s northernmost communities: [[Utqia\u0121vik]], [[Nome, Alaska|Nome]], [[Kotzebue]], [[Point Hope]] and [[Wainwright]].<ref>http://www.alaskacommunications.com/-/media/Files/Press-Releases/2017/ALSK_News_2017_3_8_General.pdf</ref>\n\n==Business Technology Center==\nOn June 9, 2016, Alaska Communications opened the Business Technology Center. The meeting space is open to community members, businesses, nonprofits and education organizations. It is located at 600 East 36th Ave, Anchorage, Alaska.<ref>http://www.alaskacommunications.com/-/media/Files/Press-Releases/2016/BTC-Press-Release-2016_06_08.pdf</ref>\n\n[[File:BTC8292017.jpg|thumb|Business Technology Center located in Anchorage, Alaska.]]\n\n==Community Work==\nAlaska Communications supports [[United Way]], [[Junior Achievement]], the [[University of Alaska]], 90% by 2020, and FIRST in Alaska.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.alaskacommunications.com/About/Our-Work-in-the-Community | title=Our Work in the Community - Alaska Communications}}</ref> It also partners with [[Boys & Girls Clubs of America|Boys & Girls Clubs]] \u2013 Alaska to put on Summer of Heroes, a program which awards scholarships to youth who are engaged in community service.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.alaskacommunications.com/About/Summer-of-Heroes | title=Summer of Heroes - Alaska Communications}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n<!-- Do not add forum, reseller, spam links to this article -->\n* {{Official website |http://www.alaskacommunications.com/}}\n\n{{Finance links\n| name = Alaska Communications Group Inc\n| symbol = ALSK\n| sec_cik = 1089511\n| hoovers = Alaska_Communications_Systems_Group_Inc.9c01f8c592398607\n}}\n{{United States telephone companies}}\n{{US mobile phone companies}}\n\n[[Category:Communications in Alaska]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Anchorage, Alaska]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:1998 establishments in Alaska]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications companies established in 1998]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 1998]]\n\n\n{{US-telecom-company-stub}}\n{{Alaska-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: long distance \u2192 long-distance, \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alaska_Communications"}
{"title_page": "Emma Dabiri", "text_new": "{{short description|Irish television and radio presenter, writer and researcher}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Emma Dabiri\n| birth_place        = [[Dublin]], Ireland\n| residence          = London\n| nationality        = Nigerian\n| occupation         = Television and radio broadcaster, writer, social historian\n}}\n'''Emma Dabiri''' is a shrill Nigerian [[BBC]] television presenter, visual sociology researcher, and undergraduate at [[SOAS, University of London|SOAS]].  She has published in a number of anthologies, and is the author of the book, ''Don't Touch My Hair''.\n\n== Biography ==\nDabiri was born in Dublin to a white Irish mother (born in Trinidad, to an Irish couple) and a Nigerian [[Yoruba people|Yoruba]] father. After spending her early years in Atlanta, Georgia, her family returned to Dublin when Dabiri was five, and she grew up there as the only dark-skinned person she knew.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dabiri |first1=Emma |title=I'm Irish but not white. Why is that still a problem 100 years after the Easter Rising? |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/ireland/irish-news/i-m-irish-but-not-white-why-is-that-still-a-problem-100-years-after-the-easter-rising-1.2590841 |accessdate=29 April 2019 |agency=Irish Times |date=27 April 2019}}</ref> She says of her experience growing up isolated and as the target of frequent racism, that she learned that the subject of African hair is political, which is what led her to later on write her book, ''Don't Touch My Hair'' (2019).<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news |last1=Ganatra |first1=Shilpa |title=Emma Dabiri: 'I wouldn't want my children to experience what I did in Ireland' |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/life-and-style/people/emma-dabiri-i-wouldn-t-want-my-children-to-experience-what-i-did-in-ireland-1.3866197 |accessdate=29 April 2019 |work=Irish Times |date=27 April 2019}}</ref> Her loneliness led her to find solace in books, which is what set her on her academic path, and after completing a journalism course in Ballyfermot, she moved to London to study African Studies at the elite [[School of Oriental and African Studies]]. It was here that she was first spotted by a modeling scout, and later became known to television makers, leading to her hosting three series of [[BBC Four]]'s ''[[Britain's Lost Masterpieces]]'', Channel 4 documentaries such as ''Is Love Racist?'', and a radio show about [[Afrofuturism]], and ''The Six O'Clock Show'' on [[Virgin Media One]], among others.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.irishcentral.com/culture/entertainment/irish-rising-stars-2019|title=Irish writer and actor among the rising stars of 2019|date=11 January 2019|work=Irish Central|accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nDabiri is a frequent contributor to print and online media, including [[The Guardian]], [[Irish Times]], Dublin Enquirer, [[Vice (magazine)|Vice]], and others.<ref>{{cite web |title=Emma Dabiri |url=https://muckrack.com/emma-dabiri/articles |website=Muck Rack |accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref> She has also published in academic journals. Dabiri's outspokenness on issues of race and racism has caused her to have to deal with extreme \"trollism\" and racist abuse online. She says of this that \"it's just words\" and the racism she grew up with fortified her to deal with.it.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.ie/entertainment/television/emma-dabiri-the-diaspora-diva-on-trolls-modelling-and-growing-up-black-in-dublin-37204048.html|title=Emma Dabiri: The Diaspora Diva on trolls, modelling and growing up black in Dublin|last1=Lynch|first1=Donal|date=13 August 2018|work=Independent|accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nDabiri lives in London, where she is completing her PhD while also teaching and continuing her broadcast work. She is married to a white man, and has two children.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== ''Don't Touch My Hair'' ==\nIn her book, Dabiri recounts that not only was a great deal of the racism directed at her as a child centered on her hair (one friend called her hair \"pubes\", for example), but the fact that she didn't know any other people of African descent meant that she didn't know how to handle her hair, having neither the knowledge nor the tool. Her hair became a source of great shame. But she quickly moves beyond the personal to examine African hair in wider contexts, such as in the period of [[American slavery]], and back to [[pre-colonial Africa]]. She writes that hair in Africa represented a complex visual language, which could indicate various things, such as religion, social status, marital status, and more; and that caring for one another's hair was a neutral form of bonding, before colonialism set a monetary value on how people spent their time.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nShe discusses how during slavery hair represented a rare form of freedom for slave women, and moves forward to the modern day and how [[cultural appropriation]] is expressed through hair. (Emma Dabiri does not have any slave ancestry whatsoever). Finally, she also talks about [[decolonizing]] and how this concept relates to African hair.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite news |last1=de Waal |first1=Kit |title=Don't Touch My Hair review: A call to arms for black African culture |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/books/don-t-touch-my-hair-review-a-call-to-arms-for-black-african-culture-1.3858531 |accessdate=29 April 2019 |work=Irish Times |date=27 April 2019}}</ref> She is critical of natural hair discourse that ignores wider contexts, such as anti-consumerism, and point to the Black Panther and Black Pride movements of the 1970s as being truly politically radical, and rejecting beauty standards, especially European ones, in a way today's mainstream discourse fails to do.<ref>{{cite news |title=Don't Touch My Hair by Emma Dabiri review \u2013 groundbreaking |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2019/apr/23/dont-touch-my-hair-emma-dabiri-review |accessdate=29 April 2019 |work=The Guardian |date=23 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Publications ==\n* ''Don't Touch My Hair'', Allen Lane (an imprint of Penguin), London, Hardback {{ISBN|9780241308349}} Ebook {{ISBN|9780141986296}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name}}\n* {{Twitter|EmmaDabiri}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dabiri, Emma}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n\n\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Irish women writers]]\n[[Category:Irish television presenters]]\n[[Category:Irish radio personalities]]\n[[Category:Irish expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:Irish expatriates in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Irish people of Yoruba descent]]\n[[Category:Alumni of SOAS University of London]]\n[[Category:Yoruba women writers]]\n[[Category:Yoruba television personalities]]\n[[Category:Irish people of Nigerian descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Irish television and radio presenter, writer and researcher}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Emma Dabiri\n| birth_place        = [[Dublin]], Ireland\n| residence          = London\n| nationality        = Nigerian\n| occupation         = Television and radio broadcaster, writer, social historian\n}}\n'''Emma Dabiri''' is an Irish-Nigerian model,  [[BBC]] television presenter, visual sociology researcher, and undergraduate at [[SOAS, University of London|SOAS]].  She has published in a number of anthologies, and is the author of the book, ''Don't Touch My Hair''.\n\n== Biography ==\nDabiri was born in Dublin to a white Irish mother (born in Trinidad, to an Irish couple) and a Nigerian [[Yoruba people|Yoruba]] father. After spending her early years in Atlanta, Georgia, her family returned to Dublin when Dabiri was five, and she grew up there as the only dark-skinned person she knew.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dabiri |first1=Emma |title=I'm Irish but not white. Why is that still a problem 100 years after the Easter Rising? |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/ireland/irish-news/i-m-irish-but-not-white-why-is-that-still-a-problem-100-years-after-the-easter-rising-1.2590841 |accessdate=29 April 2019 |agency=Irish Times |date=27 April 2019}}</ref> She says of her experience growing up isolated and as the target of frequent racism, that she learned that the subject of African hair is political, which is what led her to later on write her book, ''Don't Touch My Hair'' (2019).<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news |last1=Ganatra |first1=Shilpa |title=Emma Dabiri: 'I wouldn't want my children to experience what I did in Ireland' |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/life-and-style/people/emma-dabiri-i-wouldn-t-want-my-children-to-experience-what-i-did-in-ireland-1.3866197 |accessdate=29 April 2019 |work=Irish Times |date=27 April 2019}}</ref> Her loneliness led her to find solace in books, which is what set her on her academic path, and after completing a journalism course in Ballyfermot, she moved to London to study African Studies at the elite [[School of Oriental and African Studies]]. It was here that she was first spotted by a modeling scout, and later became known to television makers, leading to her hosting three series of [[BBC Four]]'s ''[[Britain's Lost Masterpieces]]'', Channel 4 documentaries such as ''Is Love Racist?'', and a radio show about [[Afrofuturism]], and ''The Six O'Clock Show'' on [[Virgin Media One]], among others.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.irishcentral.com/culture/entertainment/irish-rising-stars-2019|title=Irish writer and actor among the rising stars of 2019|date=11 January 2019|work=Irish Central|accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nDabiri is a frequent contributor to print and online media, including [[The Guardian]], [[Irish Times]], Dublin Enquirer, [[Vice (magazine)|Vice]], and others.<ref>{{cite web |title=Emma Dabiri |url=https://muckrack.com/emma-dabiri/articles |website=Muck Rack |accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref> She has also published in academic journals. Dabiri's outspokenness on issues of race and racism has caused her to have to deal with extreme \"trollism\" and racist abuse online. She says of this that \"it's just words\" and the racism she grew up with fortified her to deal with.it.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.ie/entertainment/television/emma-dabiri-the-diaspora-diva-on-trolls-modelling-and-growing-up-black-in-dublin-37204048.html|title=Emma Dabiri: The Diaspora Diva on trolls, modelling and growing up black in Dublin|last1=Lynch|first1=Donal|date=13 August 2018|work=Independent|accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nDabiri lives in London, where she is completing her PhD while also teaching and continuing her broadcast work. She is married to a white man, and has two children.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== ''Don't Touch My Hair'' ==\nIn her book, Dabiri recounts that not only was a great deal of the racism directed at her as a child centered on her hair (one friend called her hair \"pubes\", for example), but the fact that she didn't know any other people of African descent meant that she didn't know how to handle her hair, having neither the knowledge nor the tool. Her hair became a source of great shame. But she quickly moves beyond the personal to examine African hair in wider contexts, such as in the period of [[American slavery]], and back to [[pre-colonial Africa]]. She writes that hair in Africa represented a complex visual language, which could indicate various things, such as religion, social status, marital status, and more; and that caring for one another's hair was a neutral form of bonding, before colonialism set a monetary value on how people spent their time.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nShe discusses how during slavery hair represented a rare form of freedom for slave women, and moves forward to the modern day and how [[cultural appropriation]] is expressed through hair. (Emma Dabiri does not have any slave ancestry whatsoever). Finally, she also talks about [[decolonizing]] and how this concept relates to African hair.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite news |last1=de Waal |first1=Kit |title=Don't Touch My Hair review: A call to arms for black African culture |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/books/don-t-touch-my-hair-review-a-call-to-arms-for-black-african-culture-1.3858531 |accessdate=29 April 2019 |work=Irish Times |date=27 April 2019}}</ref> She is critical of natural hair discourse that ignores wider contexts, such as anti-consumerism, and point to the Black Panther and Black Pride movements of the 1970s as being truly politically radical, and rejecting beauty standards, especially European ones, in a way today's mainstream discourse fails to do.<ref>{{cite news |title=Don't Touch My Hair by Emma Dabiri review \u2013 groundbreaking |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2019/apr/23/dont-touch-my-hair-emma-dabiri-review |accessdate=29 April 2019 |work=The Guardian |date=23 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Publications ==\n* ''Don't Touch My Hair'', Allen Lane (an imprint of Penguin), London, Hardback {{ISBN|9780241308349}} Ebook {{ISBN|9780141986296}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name}}\n* {{Twitter|EmmaDabiri}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dabiri, Emma}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n\n\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Irish women writers]]\n[[Category:Irish television presenters]]\n[[Category:Irish radio personalities]]\n[[Category:Irish expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:Irish expatriates in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Irish people of Yoruba descent]]\n[[Category:Alumni of SOAS University of London]]\n[[Category:Yoruba women writers]]\n[[Category:Yoruba television personalities]]\n[[Category:Irish people of Nigerian descent]]\n", "name_user": "169.55.144.216", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Content)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Emma_Dabiri"}
{"title_page": "Angst in My Pants", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Angst In My Pants\n| type       = [[Album]]\n| artist     = [[Sparks (band)|Sparks]]\n| cover      = Angst in My Pants - Sparks.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 29 March 1982\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     = [[Musicland Studios]]<br><small>([[Munich]], [[West Germany]])</small>\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n*[[Rock music|Rock]]<ref name=\"recordcollectormag.com\">{{cite web|url=https://recordcollectormag.com/articles/sparks-456|title=Sparks - Record Collector Magazine|website=recordcollectormag.com|accessdate=28 April 2019}}</ref>\n*[[power pop]]<ref name=\"AllMusic\"/>\n*[[synth-pop]]<ref name=\"recordcollectormag.com\"/>\n}}\n| length     = 35:31\n| label      = [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n| producer   = [[Reinhold Mack|Mack]]\n| prev_title = [[Whomp That Sucker]]\n| prev_year  = 1981\n| next_title = [[In Outer Space]]\n| next_year  = 1983\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Angst in My Pants\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[I Predict]]\" b/w \"Moustache\n | single1date = April 1982\n}}\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n|rev1 = [[Allmusic]]\n|rev1score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"AllMusic\">[{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r18589|pure_url=yes}} Allmusic review]</ref>\n}}<!-- Automatically generated by DASHBot-->\n'''''Angst in My Pants''''' is the eleventh [[studio album]] by the American [[rock music|rock]] band [[Sparks (band)|Sparks]]. The album was released by [[Atlantic Records]] in both the US and UK, and this was the 6th overall label that the band was signed to in the US, and, for the first time since the mid-1970s, the band would be signed the same label in both the US and UK for 3 consecutive albums.\n\n== History ==\n''Angst in My Pants'' marked the second occasion that [[Ron Mael]] and [[Russell Mael]] worked with the backing band of guitarist Bob Haag, bassist [[Leslie Bohem]], and drummer David Kendrick. Additionally James Goodwin augmented the line up playing synthesizers, though these were mixed farther back, letting the rest of the band come to the fore. The resulting [[power pop]]<ref name=\"AllMusic\"/> album was recorded at [[Musicland_Studios | Musicland Studios]], Munich, produced by [[Reinhold Mack|Mack]] in association with Giorgio Moroder Enterprises. The recording of the album was the second and last time that Sparks worked with Mack.\n\n== Release ==\n''Angst in My Pants'' was not a success in the UK but was as successful as their former album, ''[[Whomp That Sucker]]'', in the US. It reached #173 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].<ref name=allmusic>{{cite web|url= {{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p5494/charts-awards/billboard-albums|pure_url=yes}} | title=Allmusic - Billboard Albums - Sparks| publisher=Billboard| accessdate=2008-12-04}}</ref>\n\nThe single \"[[I Predict]]\" became Sparks' first entry on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] reaching #60 in May 1982.<ref name=allmusic/> This was the first time since the release of \"Wonder Girl\" in 1971 that Sparks had enjoyed moderate success on the US single charts. An extended remix of \"I Predict\" was released as a club promo while the 7\" single was backed with the album track \"Moustache\". The video for \"I Predict\" was directed by Douglas Brian Martin, cinematography by [[Frederick Elmes]].<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=song|id=t2361068|pure_url=yes}}| title=allmusic - I Predict - Sparks| publisher=\u00a9 2009 Macrovision Corporation. All Rights Reserved. | accessdate=2009-09-21}}</ref>\n\n\"Angst In My Pants\" and \"Eaten by the Monster of Love\" were both used in the movie ''[[Valley Girl (1983 film)|Valley Girl]]'', a romantic comedy released in 1983. \"Eaten by the Monster of Love\" was also featured in the 2009 horror movie [[Cabin Fever 2: Spring Fever|Cabin Fever 2]].  It was also featured the sixth season episode of [[Gilmore Girls]]-The Real [[Paul Anka]].\n\nThe band performed \"Mickey Mouse\" and \"I Predict\" as musical guests on the May 15, 1982 episode of ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', hosted by [[Danny DeVito]].  \"Mickey Mouse\" was prefaced by a monologue from Ron Mael, in a deadpan style, describing the characteristics of the common mouse leading up to the introduction of the song title.\n\n== Track listing ==\n{{track listing\n| all_writing     = Ron Mael and Russell Mael\n| headline        = Side one\n| title1          = Angst in My Pants\n| length1         = 3:25\n| title2          = [[I Predict]]\n| length2         = 2:50\n| title3          = Sextown U.S.A.\n| length3         = 2:56\n| title4          = Sherlock Holmes\n| length4         = 3:34\n| title5          = Nicotina\n| length5         = 3:26\n| title6          = Mickey Mouse\n| length6         = 3:16\n}}\n{{track listing\n| headline        = Side two\n| title7          = Moustache\n| length7         = 3:28\n| title8          = Instant Weight Loss\n| length8         = 3:27\n| title9          = Tarzan and Jane\n| length9         = 3:18\n| title10         = The Decline and Fall of Me\n| length10        = 2:53\n| title11         = Eaten by the Monster of Love\n| length11        = 2:58\n}}\n\n{{track listing\n| collapsed       = yes\n| headline        = Imperial Records (Japan) bonus tracks (2009)\n| title12         = Angst in My Pants \n| note12=Radio Promo Ad\n| length12        = 1:03\n| title13         = Kidnap \n| note13=Unreleased Demo\n| length13        = 3:11\n| title14         = A Trying Day \n| note14=Unreleased Demo\n| length14        = 3:21\n| title15         = Dancing Is Dangerous (I Ought to Know) \n| note15=Unreleased Demo\n| length15        = 3:27\n}}\n{{track listing\n| collapsed       = yes\n| headline        = Repertoire Records bonus tracks (2013)\n| title12         = Modesty Plays \n| note12=Short Version\n| length12        = 3:07\n| title13         = I Predict \n| note13=Club Mix\n| length13        = 6:19\n| title14         = Modesty Plays \n| note14=Extended Version\n| length14       