ts''''' is the eleventh [[studio album]] by the American [[rock music|rock]] band [[Sparks (band)|Sparks]]. The album was released by [[Atlantic Records]] in both the US and UK, and this was the 6th overall label that the band was signed to in the US, and, for the first time since the mid-1970s, the band would be signed the same label in both the US and UK for 3 consecutive albums.\n\n== History ==\n''Angst in My Pants'' marked the second occasion that [[Ron Mael]] and [[Russell Mael]] worked with the backing band of guitarist Bob Haag, bassist [[Leslie Bohem]], and drummer David Kendrick. Additionally James Goodwin augmented the line up playing synthesizers, though these were mixed farther back, letting the rest of the band come to the fore. The resulting [[power pop]]<ref name=\"AllMusic\"/> album was recorded at [[Musicland_Studios | Musicland Studios]], Munich, produced by [[Reinhold Mack|Mack]] in association with Giorgio Moroder Enterprises. The recording of the album was the second and last time that Sparks worked with Mack.\n\n== Release ==\n''Angst in My Pants'' was not a success in the UK but was as successful as their former album, ''[[Whomp That Sucker]]'', in the US. It reached #173 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].<ref name=allmusic>{{cite web|url= {{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p5494/charts-awards/billboard-albums|pure_url=yes}} | title=Allmusic - Billboard Albums - Sparks| publisher=Billboard| accessdate=2008-12-04}}</ref>\n\nThe single \"[[I Predict]]\" became Sparks' first entry on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] reaching #60 in May 1982.<ref name=allmusic/> This was the first time since the release of \"Wonder Girl\" in 1971 that Sparks had enjoyed moderate success on the US single charts. An extended remix of \"I Predict\" was released as a club promo while the 7\" single was backed with the album track \"Moustache\". The video for \"I Predict\" was directed by Douglas Brian Martin, cinematography by [[Frederick Elmes]].<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=song|id=t2361068|pure_url=yes}}| title=allmusic - I Predict - Sparks| publisher=\u00a9 2009 Macrovision Corporation. All Rights Reserved. | accessdate=2009-09-21}}</ref>\n\n\"Angst In My Pants\" and \"Eaten by the Monster of Love\" were both used in the movie ''[[Valley Girl (1983 film)|Valley Girl]]'', a romantic comedy released in 1983. \"Eaten by the Monster of Love\" was also featured in the 2009 horror movie [[Cabin Fever 2: Spring Fever|Cabin Fever 2]].  It was also featured the sixth season episode of [[Gilmore Girls]]-The Real [[Paul Anka]].\n\n\"Mickey Mouse,\" while not charting, was performed by the band as they appeared as musical guests on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', hosted by [[Danny DeVito]].  This episode aired on NBC May 15, 1982.  The song was prefaced by a monologue from Ron Mael, in a deadpan style, describing the characteristics of the common mouse leading up to the introduction of the song title.  The band also performed a second cut from the album: \"[[I Predict]].\"\n\n== Track listing ==\n{{track listing\n| all_writing     = Ron Mael and Russell Mael\n| headline        = Side one\n| title1          = Angst in My Pants\n| length1         = 3:25\n| title2          = [[I Predict]]\n| length2         = 2:50\n| title3          = Sextown U.S.A.\n| length3         = 2:56\n| title4          = Sherlock Holmes\n| length4         = 3:34\n| title5          = Nicotina\n| length5         = 3:26\n| title6          = Mickey Mouse\n| length6         = 3:16\n}}\n{{track listing\n| headline        = Side two\n| title7          = Moustache\n| length7         = 3:28\n| title8          = Instant Weight Loss\n| length8         = 3:27\n| title9          = Tarzan and Jane\n| length9         = 3:18\n| title10         = The Decline and Fall of Me\n| length10        = 2:53\n| title11         = Eaten by the Monster of Love\n| length11        = 2:58\n}}\n\n{{track listing\n| collapsed       = yes\n| headline        = Imperial Records (Japan) bonus tracks (2009)\n| title12         = Angst in My Pants \n| note12=Radio Promo Ad\n| length12        = 1:03\n| title13         = Kidnap \n| note13=Unreleased Demo\n| length13        = 3:11\n| title14         = A Trying Day \n| note14=Unreleased Demo\n| length14        = 3:21\n| title15         = Dancing Is Dangerous (I Ought to Know) \n| note15=Unreleased Demo\n| length15        = 3:27\n}}\n{{track listing\n| collapsed       = yes\n| headline        = Repertoire Records bonus tracks (2013)\n| title12         = Modesty Plays \n| note12=Short Version\n| length12        = 3:07\n| title13         = I Predict \n| note13=Club Mix\n| length13        = 6:19\n| title14         = Modesty Plays \n| note14=Extended Version\n| length14        = 5:16\n}}\n\n== Personnel ==\n* [[Russell Mael]] - vocals\n* [[Ron Mael]] - keyboards, synthesizers, cover concept\n* [[Leslie Bohem]] - bass guitar, additional background vocals\n* Bob Haag - guitar, additional background vocals\n* David Kendrick - drums\n* James Goodwin - synthesizers\n* [[Reinhold Mack|Mack]] - production, engineering, synthesizer programming\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Sparks}}\n\n[[Category:Sparks (band) albums]]\n[[Category:1982 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Reinhold Mack]]\n[[Category:Atlantic Records albums]]\n[[Category:Carrere Records albums]]\n[[Category:Oglio Records albums]]\n[[Category:Repertoire Records albums]]\n", "name_user": "Mab987", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRelease", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angst_in_My_Pants"}
{"title_page": "Plandi\u0161te", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=March 2013}}\n{{unreliable sources|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                     = Plandi\u0161te\n| native_name              = \u041f\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0438\u0448\u0442\u0435\n| image_skyline            = Plandi\u0161te,_Orthodox_church.jpg\n| imagesize                = 300px\n| image_caption            = The new Orthodox church\n| image_flag               =\n| image_shield             = COA_Plandiste.png\n| image_map                = Municipalities of Serbia Plandi\u0161te.png\n| map_caption              = Location of Plandi\u0161te within Serbia\n| settlement_type          = [[List of cities in Serbia|Village]] and [[Municipalities and cities of Serbia|municipality]]\n| subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name         = {{flag|Serbia}}\n| subdivision_type1        = [[Subdivisions of Serbia|Province]]\n| subdivision_name1        = [[Vojvodina]]\n| subdivision_type2        = [[Districts of Serbia|District]]\n| subdivision_name2        = [[South Banat District|South Banat]]\n| subdivision_type3        = [[Municipalities of Serbia|Municipalities]]\n| subdivision_name3        =\n| leader_title             = Mayor\n| leader_name              = Milan Selakovi\u0107\n| established_title        =\n| established_date         =\n| area_magnitude           =\n| area_total_sq_mi         =\n| population_as_of         = 2011\n| population_footnotes     =\n| total_type               = Plandi\u0161te\n| population_total         = 3832\n| population_density_km2   =\n| population_density_sq_mi =\n| population_metro         = 11336\n| population_blank1_title  = [[Demonym]]\n| population_blank2        =\n| timezone                 = [[Central European Time|CET]]\n| utc_offset               = +1\n| timezone_DST             = [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n| utc_offset_DST           = +2\n| coordinates              = {{coord|45|13|37|N|21|7|18|E|region:RS|display=inline,title}}\n| elevation_footnotes      =\n| elevation_m              = 79\n| elevation_ft             =\n| postal_code_type         = Postal code\n| postal_code              = 26360\n| area_code                = [[Telephone numbers in Serbia|+381(0)13]]\n| website                  = www.plandiste.com\n| blank_name               = [[Vehicle registration plates of Serbia|Car plates]]\n| blank_info               = V\u0160\n}} <!-- Infobox ends -->\n[[File:Plandiste mun.png|right|thumb|280px|Map of Plandi\u0161te municipality]]\n'''Plandi\u0161te''' ({{Lang-sr-Cyrl|\u041f\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0438\u0448\u0442\u0435}}, {{IPA-sh|pl\u00e2ndi\u02d0\u0283te|pron}}) is a village and municipality located in the [[South Banat District]] of the autonomous province of [[Vojvodina]], Serbia. The village has a population of 3,832, while Plandi\u0161te municipality has 11,336 inhabitants. One of municipality's best known landmarks is [[Kapetanovo Castle]], located in [[Stari Lec]].\n\n==Name==\nIn [[Serbian language|Serbian]], the village is known as \u041f\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0438\u0448\u0442\u0435 or ''Plandi\u0161te'', in [[Romanian language|Romanian]] as ''Plandi\u0219te'', in [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]] as ''Zichyfalva'', in [[German language|German]] as ''Zichydorf'' {{IPA-de|Z\u026ad\u0292idorf|pron}} , and in {{lang-mk|\u041f\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0438\u0448\u0442\u0435}}.\n\nThe name of the village derived from the word ''plandovati'' used in the local Serbian dialect, which in modern standard Serbian means ''odmarati'', and in English means ''to rest''.\n\n==History==\n=== World Politics running over Banat for centuries ===\nBanat as part of [[Pannonia]] was under [[Roman Empire|Roman]] rule from 9 BC to the end of the 4th century.<ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hungary#Before_895{{unreliable source?|date=April 2020}}</ref> In 5th century the [[Huns]] razed the land. In the 9th century, the Hungarian empire started its reign, and around 1000 AD the Banat became part of the prospering Hungarian empire. In the 13th century [[Genghis Khan]] invaded Europe. After the [[Battle of Moh\u00e1cs]] in 1526, the [[Ottoman|Turks]] took over two-thirds of Hungary, including Banat.\n\n=== Settlements before Zichydorf ===\nIn the municipal area of Plandi\u0161te have been several places in medieval times: Bioseg, Terjan, Sarkac and Raros. These names still exist on 18th-century maps <ref>https://mapire.eu/de/map/secondsurvey-hungary/embed/?bbox=2343817.2621939667%2C5657190.455042724%2C2362047.493439981%2C5662923.232164111&map-list=1&layers=5</ref>. \n\nAccording to Milleker<ref>http://zichydorf.ferienwohnung-otterberg.de/Zichydorf/geschichte.htm</ref> there were several different villages named Bioseg between 1375<ref>Pesti: Krasso, III, Nr. 86</ref> and 1550<ref>Pesty: Krasso, IV, Nr. 405</ref>. They were named O-Belzeg, Nagy-Belzeg und Pervan-Belzeg. The names mean: \n\n* Prefix ''bel-'' or ''bio-'' comes from Serbian ''belu'' which means white (compare to [[Belgrade]] / Beograd).\n* ''-zeg'' comes from Hungarian ''sziget'' meaning [[island]].\n* ''Pervan'' is Serbian and means ''first'', which is common at that time and area to distinct different places of the same name: simply give numbers.\n* Milleker does not tell anything about ''O-''. Maybe it is nothing more than a guess: in German it is common to abbreviate ''Ober'' with ''O-'' meaning the village located on higher altitude.\n* ''Nagy'' is Hungarian and means ''big''.\n\nWhat happened to the villages during the reign of the Ottoman is unknown. When the Hungarians came back, of those villages only a few houses and the names were left. \n\nMilleker<ref>http://zichydorf.ferienwohnung-otterberg.de/Zichydorf/geschichte.htm</ref> talks about a [[legend]], that at the today location of Plandi\u0161te there had been a [[battle]] between [[Prince_Eugene_of_Savoy|Prince Eugene]] and the Ottoman Empire during the [[Great_Turkish_War|Great Turkish War (1683-1699)]] most likely around 1686 (TODO check). What remained was a graveyard, which was discovered in 1889 during the erection of the train line from [[Zrenjanin]] to [[Margita]]. He suggests that Romanian [[Shepherd]]s founded Mormin\u021b which means cemetery in Romanian and thus might refer to exactly this battle and graveyard.\n\nFact is, in 1713 the village Mormin\u021b exists at the location of Plandi\u0161te with a count of 23 houses. <ref>Glasnik Jahrgang V, Nr 10, S. 15 1</ref> After the [[Austro-Turkish_War_(1716\u20131718)|Austro-Turkish War (1716\u20131718)]], it counted only 8<ref>Szenkl\u00e4ray: Sz\u00e4s ev, 1, 26</ref>. In 1738 the Ottoman Turks stroke back destroying settlements along the Danube, including Mormin\u021b. The Turks advanced north over the next year, all the way to [[Temesvar]], the capital of Banat. After this invasion, the territory around Mormin\u021b was abandoned<ref>Szenkl\u00e4ray: Sz\u00e4s Beilage 6, S. 5</ref>.\n\n=== Austrians driving back the Ottoman ===\nThe Austrians and Hungarians joined forces and in 1738 pushed the Turks back south, across the Danube. The expulsion of the Turks brought organized settlement under the auspices of Habsburg. Austro-Hungarian military campaigns were based on German nobility - Counts, who served as generals to the Imperial Austrian Army. It was custom for the Austrian [[Emperor|Kaiser]] to reward each count with a piece of land from the newly conquered Banat. So Count Carl Zichy de V\u00e1sonke\u00f6, at that time [[president]] of the Hungarian Parliament (check! Milleker calls it \"Kammer\", maybe https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hofkammer{{unreliable source?|date=April 2020}}), became the owner of about 10,000 [[acres]] (check, usually they counted in [[Austrian]] Katastraljoch which is 0.57 [[ha]]) of land in the Plandi\u0161te area. Since he did not earn much money from the [[lease]] of this land he decided to take part in the colonization effort<ref>http://zichydorf.ferienwohnung-otterberg.de/Zichydorf/geschichte.htm</ref>. \n\n=== Colonizing the Conquered Land ===\nIn 1782 [[Joseph_II,_Holy_Roman_Emperor|Emperor Joseph II]] started the third colonization into Banat which ended in 1787 <ref>https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schwabenzug#Dritter_gro%C3%9Fer_Schwabenzug_(1781%E2%80%931787){{unreliable source?|date=April 2020}}</ref>. Too late, in winter 1787 and spring 1788 the colony Zichydorf was established<ref>http://zichydorf.ferienwohnung-otterberg.de/Zichydorf/geschichte.htm</ref>. So they settled it with people from German Banat villages instead: [[Graba\u021b]], [[Jimbolia]] (Hatzfeld), [[Comlo\u0219u Mic]] (Ostern), [[Iecea Mic\u0103]] (Klein-Jetscha) and [[Iecea Mare]] (Gro\u00df-Jetscha). The new settlement consisted of 123 houses owning 34 [[Katastraljoch]]<ref>https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alte_Ma%C3%9Fe_und_Gewichte_(%C3%96sterreich)#Fl%C3%A4chenma%C3%9Fe{{unreliable source?|date=April 2020}}</ref> (19,5 [[Hectare|ha]]) each. \n\nIn 1867 Austria adopted a dual monarchy known as the Austro-Hungarian Empire. The Hungarian authorities later forced [[Magyarization]] to create a special Hungarian nation from a mixed population, which was mostly German, but also included Romanians, Serbs, Turks and several other ethnics. Magyarization resulted in the name change from German to Hungarian. So Zichydorf was renamed to Zichyfalva or Zichyhaza. Also, the Hungarians built a lot of infrastructure like railroads and the [[Danube\u2013Tisa\u2013Danube Canal]].\n\n=== Modern times ===\nAfter the [[Treaty of Versailles]] in 1918 the new borders brought Zichyfalva into the state of Serbia, which became part of the newly formed [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia]]. [[Alexander I of Yugoslavia]] proclaimed the change of all place names to Serbian and so it was named Mariolana.\n\nDuring the German occupation in the [[Second World War]] the names of the settlements were returned to the German original names. Afterwards the place got its present name Plandi\u0161te. Immigrants from other parts of the country arrived on the territory of the municipality, so that 18 ethnicities were represented in the again multi-ethnic population structure.\n\n==Inhabited places==\nPlandi\u0161te municipality includes the following villages:\n*Plandi\u0161te\n*[[Banatski Sokolac]]\n*[[Barice, Plandi\u0161te|Barice]]\n*[[Velika Greda]]\n*[[Veliki Gaj]]\n*[[Du\u017eine]]\n*[[Jermenovci]]\n*[[Kupinik (Plandi\u0161te)|Kupinik]]\n*[[Laudonovac]]\n*[[Margita (Plandi\u0161te)|Margita]]\n*[[Markovi\u0107evo]]\n*[[Mileti\u0107evo]]\n*[[Stari Lec]]\n*[[Hajdu\u010dica]]\n\n==Demographics==\nHistorical population of the village:\n{{historical populations\n|align=none\n| cols = 2\n|1869|2,937\n|1880|2,636\n|1890|3,128\n|1900|3,192\n|1910|2,846\n|1921|3,120\n|1931|3,281\n|1948|3,040\n|1953|3,096\n|1961|3,509\n|1971|3,769\n|1981|4,122\n}}\n\n===Ethnic groups===\n;Municipality\n{{See also|Serbs in Vojvodina|Hungarians in Vojvodina|Macedonians in Serbia|Romani people of Vojvodina|Romanians in Vojvodina|Slovaks in Vojvodina|Serbian lands|List of Hungarian communities in Vojvodina}}\nAccording to the 2011 census, the municipality of Plandi\u0161te had a total population of 11,336, including:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://webrzs.stat.gov.rs/WebSite/Public/ReportResultView.aspx?rptKey=indId%3d18020101IND01%26102%3d80349%2636%3d0%2cG%2cO%2623%3d0%26111%3d01%2c02%2c03%2c04%2c05%2c06%2c07%2c08%2c09%2c10%2c11%2c12%2c13%2c14%2c15%2c16%2c17%2c18%2c19%2c20%2c21%2c22%2c23%2c24%2c25%2c26%26sAreaId%3d18020101%26dType%3dIdentificatorAndName%26lType%3dEnglish|title=Population by ethnicity \u2013 Plandi\u0161te|publisher=Statistical Office of the Republic of Serbia (SORS)|accessdate=4 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n*5,868 [[Serbs]] (51.76%)\n*1,280 [[Magyars|Hungarians]] (11.29%)\n*1,042 [[Macedonians (ethnic group)|Macedonians]] (9.19%)\n*784 [[Romanians]] (7.92%)\n*616 [[Slovaks]] (5.43%)\n*281 [[Romani people|Romani]] (2.48%)\n*1,465 Others and undeclared (12.92%)\n\nSettlements with '''Serb''' ethnic majority are: Plandi\u0161te, [[Banatski Sokolac]], [[Velika Greda]], [[Veliki Gaj]], [[Du\u017eine]], [[Kupinik (Plandi\u0161te)|Kupinik]], [[Laudonovac]], [[Markovi\u0107evo]], [[Mileti\u0107evo]], and [[Stari Lec]]. The settlement with '''Romanian''' ethnic majority is [[Barice, Plandi\u0161te|Barice]]. The settlement with '''Hungarian''' ethnic majority is [[Jermenovci]]. Ethnically mixed settlement with relative '''Serb''' majority is [[Margita (Plandi\u0161te)|Margita]]. Ethnically mixed settlement with relative '''Slovak''' majority is [[Hajdu\u010dica]].\n\n;Village\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Total\n! [[Serbs]]\n! [[Macedonians (ethnic group)|Macedonians]]\n! [[Yugoslavs]]\n! [[Hungarians]]\n! [[Romanians]]\n! [[Slovaks]]\n! [[Montenegrins (ethnic group)|Montenegrins]]\n! Unknown\n|-\n| 1991\n| 4,380\n| 54.84%\n| 23.69%\n| 9.2%\n| 5.57%\n| 1.57%\n| 0.82%\n| 0.66%\n| 3.65%\n|-\n| 2002\n| 4,270\n| 59.46%\n| 21.31%\n| 3.93%\n| 5.69%\n| 1.7%\n| 0.96%\n| 0.42%\n| 6.53%\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of places in Serbia]]\n*[[List of cities, towns and villages in Vojvodina]]\n*[[Municipalities of Serbia]]\n*[[South Banat District]]\n*[https://www.yumpu.com/de/document/view/21282907/geschichte-der-gemeinde-zichydorf-von-j-achtzehner-zichydorfh- Geschichte der Gemeinde Zichydorf] by Johann Achtzehner\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Queen_of_the_Rosary_Roman_Catholic_church,_Plandi\u0161te,_Vojvodina,_Serbia_-_20060826.jpg|The center of the village and the old Catholic Church\nFile:Kapetanovo.jpg|Kapetanovo Castle in Stari Lec\nFile:New orthodox church Crkva Sveti Rafailo Banatski.jpg|New orthodox church\nFile:House of Family Wosching built about 1890.jpg|House Wosching built about 1890\n</gallery>\n{{commons category|Plandi\u0161te}}\n{{South Banat District}}\n{{Municipalities of Serbia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Plandiste}}\n[[Category:Populated places in Serbian Banat]]\n[[Category:Populated places in South Banat District]]\n[[Category:Municipalities and cities of Vojvodina]]\n[[Category:South Banat District]]\n[[Category:Plandi\u0161te| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=March 2013}}\n{{unreliable sources|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                     = Plandi\u0161te\n| native_name              = \u041f\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0438\u0448\u0442\u0435\n| image_skyline            = Plandi\u0161te,_Orthodox_church.jpg\n| imagesize                = 300px\n| image_caption            = The new Orthodox church\n| image_flag               =\n| image_shield             = COA_Plandiste.png\n| image_map                = Municipalities of Serbia Plandi\u0161te.png\n| map_caption              = Location of Plandi\u0161te within Serbia\n| settlement_type          = [[List of cities in Serbia|Village]] and [[Municipalities and cities of Serbia|municipality]]\n| subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name         = {{flag|Serbia}}\n| subdivision_type1        = [[Subdivisions of Serbia|Province]]\n| subdivision_name1        = [[Vojvodina]]\n| subdivision_type2        = [[Districts of Serbia|District]]\n| subdivision_name2        = [[South Banat District|South Banat]]\n| subdivision_type3        = [[Municipalities of Serbia|Municipalities]]\n| subdivision_name3        =\n| leader_title             = Mayor\n| leader_name              = Milan Selakovi\u0107\n| established_title        =\n| established_date         =\n| area_magnitude           =\n| area_total_sq_mi         =\n| population_as_of         = 2011\n| population_footnotes     =\n| total_type               = Plandi\u0161te\n| population_total         = 3832\n| population_density_km2   =\n| population_density_sq_mi =\n| population_metro         = 11336\n| population_blank1_title  = [[Demonym]]\n| population_blank2        =\n| timezone                 = [[Central European Time|CET]]\n| utc_offset               = +1\n| timezone_DST             = [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n| utc_offset_DST           = +2\n| coordinates              = {{coord|45|13|37|N|21|7|18|E|region:RS|display=inline,title}}\n| elevation_footnotes      =\n| elevation_m              = 79\n| elevation_ft             =\n| postal_code_type         = Postal code\n| postal_code              = 26360\n| area_code                = [[Telephone numbers in Serbia|+381(0)13]]\n| website                  = www.plandiste.com\n| blank_name               = [[Vehicle registration plates of Serbia|Car plates]]\n| blank_info               = V\u0160\n}} <!-- Infobox ends -->\n[[File:Plandiste mun.png|right|thumb|280px|Map of Plandi\u0161te municipality]]\n'''Plandi\u0161te''' ({{Lang-sr-Cyrl|\u041f\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0438\u0448\u0442\u0435}}, {{IPA-sh|pl\u00e2ndi\u02d0\u0283te|pron}}) is a village and municipality located in the [[South Banat District]] of the autonomous province of [[Vojvodina]], Serbia. The village has a population of 3,832, while Plandi\u0161te municipality has 11,336 inhabitants. One of municipality's best known landmarks is [[Kapetanovo Castle]], located in [[Stari Lec]].\n\n==Name==\nIn [[Serbian language|Serbian]], the village is known as \u041f\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0438\u0448\u0442\u0435 or ''Plandi\u0161te'', in [[Romanian language|Romanian]] as ''Plandi\u0219te'', in [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]] as ''Zichyfalva'', in [[German language|German]] as ''Zichydorf'' {{IPA-de|Z\u026ad\u0292idorf|pron}} , and in {{lang-mk|\u041f\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0438\u0448\u0442\u0435}}.\n\nThe name of the village derived from the word \"plandovati\" used in the local Serbian dialect, which in modern standard Serbian means \"odmarati\", and in English means \"to rest\".\n\n==History==\n=== World Politics running over Banat for centuries ===\nBanat as part of [[Pannonia]] was under [[Roman Empire|Roman]] rule from 9 BC to the end of the 4th century<ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hungary#Before_895{{unreliable source?|date=April 2020}}</ref>. In 5th century the [[Huns]] razed the land. In the 9th century the Hungarian empire started it's career and around 1000 AD the Banat became part of the prospering Hungarian empire. In 13th century [[Genghis Khan]] invaded Europe. After the [[Battle of Moh\u00e1cs]] in 1526, the [[Ottoman|Turks]] took over two thirds of Hungary, including Banat.\n\n=== Settlements before Zichydorf ===\nIn the municipal area of Plandi\u0161te have been several places in medieval times: Bioseg, Terjan, Sarkac and Raros. These names still exist on 18th century maps <ref>https://mapire.eu/de/map/secondsurvey-hungary/embed/?bbox=2343817.2621939667%2C5657190.455042724%2C2362047.493439981%2C5662923.232164111&map-list=1&layers=5</ref>. \n\nAccording to Milleker<ref>http://zichydorf.ferienwohnung-otterberg.de/Zichydorf/geschichte.htm</ref> there were several different villages named Bioseg between 1375<ref>Pesti: Krasso, III, Nr. 86</ref> and 1550<ref>Pesty: Krasso, IV, Nr. 405</ref>. They were named O-Belzeg, Nagy-Belzeg und Pervan-Belzeg. The names mean: \n\n* Prefix ''bel-'' or ''bio-'' comes from Serbian ''belu'' which means white (compare to [[Belgrade]] / Beograd).\n* ''-zeg'' comes from Hungarian ''sziget'' meaning [[island]].\n* Pervan is serbian and means first, which is common at that time and area to distinct different places of the same name: simply give numbers.\n* Milleker doesnt't tell anything about ''O-''. Maybe it's nothing more than a guess: in German it's common to abbreviate ''Ober'' with ''O-'' meaning the village located on higher altitude.\n* ''Nagy'' is Huangarian and means ''big''.\n\nWhat happend to the villages during the reign of the Ottoman is unknown. When the Hungarians came back, of those villages only a few houses and the names were left. \n\nMilleker<ref>http://zichydorf.ferienwohnung-otterberg.de/Zichydorf/geschichte.htm</ref> talks about a [[legend]], that at the today location of Plandi\u0161te there had been a [[battle]] between [[Prince_Eugene_of_Savoy|Prince Eugene]] and the Ottoman Empire during the [[Great_Turkish_War|Great Turkish War (1683-1699)]] most likely around 1686 (TODO check). What remained was a graveyard, which was discovered in 1889 during the erection of the train line from [[Zrenjanin]] to [[Margita]]. He suggests that Romanian [[Shepherd]]s founded Mormin\u021b which means cemetery in Romanian and thus might refer to exactly this battle and graveyard.\n\nFact is, in 1713 the village Mormin\u021b exists at the location of Plandi\u0161te with a count of 23 houses. <ref>Glasnik Jahrgang V, Nr 10, S. 15 1</ref> After the [[Austro-Turkish_War_(1716\u20131718)|Austro-Turkish War (1716\u20131718)]], it counted only 8<ref>Szenkl\u00e4ray: Sz\u00e4s ev, 1, 26</ref>. In 1738 the Ottoman Turks stroke back destroying settlements along the Danube, including Mormin\u021b. The Turks advanced north over the next year, all the way to [[Temesvar]], the capital of Banat. After this invasion, the territory around Mormin\u021b was abandoned<ref>Szenkl\u00e4ray: Sz\u00e4s Beilage 6, S. 5</ref>.\n\n=== Austrians driving back the Ottoman ===\nThe Austrians and Hungarians joined forces and in 1738 pushed the Turks back south, across the Danube. The expulsion of the Turks brought organized settlement under the auspices of Habsburg. Austro-Hungarian military campaigns were based on German nobility - Counts, who served as generals to the Imperial Austrian Army. It was custom for the Austrian [[Emperor|Kaiser]] to reward each count with a piece of land from the newly conquered Banat. So Count Carl Zichy de V\u00e1sonke\u00f6, at that time [[president]] of the Hungarian Parliament (check! Milleker calls it \"Kammer\", maybe https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hofkammer{{unreliable source?|date=April 2020}}), became the owner of about 10,000 [[acres]] (check, usually they counted in [[Austrian]] Katastraljoch which is 0.57 [[ha]]) of land in the Plandi\u0161te area. Since he did not earn much money from the [[lease]] of this land he decided to take part in the colonization effort<ref>http://zichydorf.ferienwohnung-otterberg.de/Zichydorf/geschichte.htm</ref>. \n\n=== Colonizing the Conquered Land ===\nIn 1782 [[Joseph_II,_Holy_Roman_Emperor|Emperor Joseph II]] started the third colonization into Banat which ended in 1787 <ref>https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schwabenzug#Dritter_gro%C3%9Fer_Schwabenzug_(1781%E2%80%931787){{unreliable source?|date=April 2020}}</ref>. Too late, in winter 1787 and spring 1788 the colony Zichydorf was established<ref>http://zichydorf.ferienwohnung-otterberg.de/Zichydorf/geschichte.htm</ref>. So they settled it with people from German Banat villages instead: [[Graba\u021b]], [[Jimbolia]] (Hatzfeld), [[Comlo\u0219u Mic]] (Ostern), [[Iecea Mic\u0103]] (Klein-Jetscha) and [[Iecea Mare]] (Gro\u00df-Jetscha). The new settlement consisted of 123 houses owning 34 [[Katastraljoch]]<ref>https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alte_Ma%C3%9Fe_und_Gewichte_(%C3%96sterreich)#Fl%C3%A4chenma%C3%9Fe{{unreliable source?|date=April 2020}}</ref> (19,5 [[Hectare|ha]]) each. \n\nIn 1867 Austria adopted a dual monarchy known as the Austro-Hungarian Empire. The Hungarian authorities later forced [[Magyarization]] to create a special Hungarian nation from a mixed population, which was mostly German, but also included Romanians, Serbs and Turks and several other ethnics. Magyarization resulted in the name change from German to Hungarian. So Zichydorf was renamed to Zichyfalva or Zichyhaza. Also the Hungarians built a lot of infrastructure like railroads and the [[Danube\u2013Tisa\u2013Danube Canal]].\n\n=== Modern times ===\nAfter the [[Treaty of Versailles]] in 1918 the new borders brought Zichyfalva into the state of Serbia, which became part of the newly formed [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia]]. [[Alexander I of Yugoslavia]] proclaimed the change of all place names to Serbian and so it was named Mariolana.\n\nDuring the German occupation in the [[Second World War]] the names of the settlements were returned to the German original names. Afterwards the place got it's present name Plandi\u0161te. Immigrants from other parts of the country arrived on the territory of the municipality, so that 18 ethnicities were represented in the again multi-ethnic population structure.\n\n==Inhabited places==\nPlandi\u0161te municipality includes the following villages:\n*Plandi\u0161te\n*[[Banatski Sokolac]]\n*[[Barice, Plandi\u0161te|Barice]]\n*[[Velika Greda]]\n*[[Veliki Gaj]]\n*[[Du\u017eine]]\n*[[Jermenovci]]\n*[[Kupinik (Plandi\u0161te)|Kupinik]]\n*[[Laudonovac]]\n*[[Margita (Plandi\u0161te)|Margita]]\n*[[Markovi\u0107evo]]\n*[[Mileti\u0107evo]]\n*[[Stari Lec]]\n*[[Hajdu\u010dica]]\n\n==Demographics==\nHistorical population of the village:\n{{historical populations\n|align=none\n| cols = 2\n|1869|2,937\n|1880|2,636\n|1890|3,128\n|1900|3,192\n|1910|2,846\n|1921|3,120\n|1931|3,281\n|1948|3,040\n|1953|3,096\n|1961|3,509\n|1971|3,769\n|1981|4,122\n}}\n\n===Ethnic groups===\n;Municipality\n{{See also|Serbs in Vojvodina|Hungarians in Vojvodina|Macedonians in Serbia|Romani people of Vojvodina|Romanians in Vojvodina|Slovaks in Vojvodina|Serbian lands|List of Hungarian communities in Vojvodina}}\nAccording to the 2011 census, the municipality of Plandi\u0161te had a total population of 11,336, including:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://webrzs.stat.gov.rs/WebSite/Public/ReportResultView.aspx?rptKey=indId%3d18020101IND01%26102%3d80349%2636%3d0%2cG%2cO%2623%3d0%26111%3d01%2c02%2c03%2c04%2c05%2c06%2c07%2c08%2c09%2c10%2c11%2c12%2c13%2c14%2c15%2c16%2c17%2c18%2c19%2c20%2c21%2c22%2c23%2c24%2c25%2c26%26sAreaId%3d18020101%26dType%3dIdentificatorAndName%26lType%3dEnglish|title=Population by ethnicity \u2013 Plandi\u0161te|publisher=Statistical Office of the Republic of Serbia (SORS)|accessdate=4 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n*5,868 [[Serbs]] (51.76%)\n*1,280 [[Magyars|Hungarians]] (11.29%)\n*1,042 [[Macedonians (ethnic group)|Macedonians]] (9.19%)\n*784 [[Romanians]] (7.92%)\n*616 [[Slovaks]] (5.43%)\n*281 [[Romani people|Romani]] (2.48%)\n*1,465 Others and undeclared (12.92%)\n\nSettlements with '''Serb''' ethnic majority are: Plandi\u0161te, [[Banatski Sokolac]], [[Velika Greda]], [[Veliki Gaj]], [[Du\u017eine]], [[Kupinik (Plandi\u0161te)|Kupinik]], [[Laudonovac]], [[Markovi\u0107evo]], [[Mileti\u0107evo]], and [[Stari Lec]]. The settlement with '''Romanian''' ethnic majority is [[Barice, Plandi\u0161te|Barice]]. The settlement with '''Hungarian''' ethnic majority is [[Jermenovci]]. Ethnically mixed settlement with relative '''Serb''' majority is [[Margita (Plandi\u0161te)|Margita]]. Ethnically mixed settlement with relative '''Slovak''' majority is [[Hajdu\u010dica]].\n\n;Village\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Total\n! [[Serbs]]\n! [[Macedonians (ethnic group)|Macedonians]]\n! [[Yugoslavs]]\n! [[Hungarians]]\n! [[Romanians]]\n! [[Slovaks]]\n! [[Montenegrins (ethnic group)|Montenegrins]]\n! Unknown\n|-\n| 1991\n| 4,380\n| 54.84%\n| 23.69%\n| 9.2%\n| 5.57%\n| 1.57%\n| 0.82%\n| 0.66%\n| 3.65%\n|-\n| 2002\n| 4,270\n| 59.46%\n| 21.31%\n| 3.93%\n| 5.69%\n| 1.7%\n| 0.96%\n| 0.42%\n| 6.53%\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of places in Serbia]]\n*[[List of cities, towns and villages in Vojvodina]]\n*[[Municipalities of Serbia]]\n*[[South Banat District]]\n*[https://www.yumpu.com/de/document/view/21282907/geschichte-der-gemeinde-zichydorf-von-j-achtzehner-zichydorfh- Geschichte der Gemeinde Zichydorf] by Johann Achtzehner\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Queen_of_the_Rosary_Roman_Catholic_church,_Plandi\u0161te,_Vojvodina,_Serbia_-_20060826.jpg|The center of the village and the old Catholic Church\nFile:Kapetanovo.jpg|Kapetanovo Castle in Stari Lec\nFile:New orthodox church Crkva Sveti Rafailo Banatski.jpg|New orthodox church\nFile:House of Family Wosching built about 1890.jpg|House Wosching built about 1890\n</gallery>\n{{commons category|Plandi\u0161te}}\n{{South Banat District}}\n{{Municipalities of Serbia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Plandiste}}\n[[Category:Populated places in Serbian Banat]]\n[[Category:Populated places in South Banat District]]\n[[Category:Municipalities and cities of Vojvodina]]\n[[Category:South Banat District]]\n[[Category:Plandi\u0161te| ]]\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comment": "copy edit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plandi%C5%A1te"}
